						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-80-4esit",
							"style": "h3",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-79-1zkwm",
									"text": "WHAT TO DO:",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-82-bxgfd",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "number",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-81-df0hw",
									"text": "Install all three applications."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-86-yhmwc",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "number",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-83-e6m3g",
									"text": "Open LineIn. Select your recording device from the ‘input’ drop down menu, and select ‘soundflower (2 ch)’ from the output dropdown menu. Then press the ‘play thru’ button.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-84-q986z",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_6151\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"456\"]"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-85-9lf2f",
									"text": " Sample view of the LineIn application[/caption]"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-88-borso",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "number",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-87-kuwmg",
									"text": "In your video/audio chat tool, open your settings and set your speakers to ‘Soundflower 2ch’. This will send the incoming audio from your guests to the Soundflower 2ch stream, where your mic is also being set (effectively making them one channel)."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-92-q2eg1",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "number",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-89-0k3bx",
									"text": "Open soundflowerbed. Under ‘Soundflower (2ch)’, select ‘built-in output’. This will let you listen to the pseudo-single channel mix on your headphones (for monitoring purposes) while you record. You should hear yourself and your guests through your headphones. Your own voice may have a slight delay, which you may be able to reduce slightly by changing the buffering settings in Soundflower.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-90-ognro",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_6150\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"242\"]"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-91-udcev",
									"text": " View of the Soundflower controls (they’ll appear in the Mac OS menu bar at the top of your screen)[/caption]"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-96-h8u6i",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "number",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-93-ytv1i",
									"text": "Open Audacity. Make sure the recording source is set to Soundflower (2ch). Start a call and start recording — the recording should pick up both your audio (routed from your mic to Soundflower 2ch by Linein and your other participants audio (send to Soundflower 2ch by your chat applications settings). There’s a few more little things you can do to tweak settings and all that, but that’s basically it.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-94-75urt",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_6149\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"357\"]"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-95-bx8aj",
									"text": " View of the recording dropdown in Audacity[/caption]"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-98-lysve",
							"style": "h3",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-97-mnmuc",
									"text": "OTHER TIPS:",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-100-jpt0f",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "bullet",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-99-hryca",
									"text": "The sound quality of your recording will depend on two things: the recording instrument you use (a dedicated external microphone will almost always sound better than your laptop’s built-in recording device) and the quality of your video/audio connection (when we’ve had more than 2 people in a call and had buffering/stuttering issues, we’ve had participants mute their video and the audio issues usually resolve)."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-118-853vk",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "bullet",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-101-uxyxc",
									"text": "Recording equipment. ",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-102-dext4",
									"text": "If you’re going to be doing this for a while, I’d recommend buying a nice microphone. There are two ways to approach this. If you’ll always be recording with your computer present, get a nice simple USB mic. "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-104-qd6qr",
									"text": "Blue",
									"marks": [
										"key-103-fw0v4"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-105-axlh1",
									"text": " makes good microphones — you can get either the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-107-hhrww",
									"text": "Snowball",
									"marks": [
										"key-106-ku5ut"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-108-vcrdl",
									"text": " (~$50) or the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-110-pxgqm",
									"text": "Yeti",
									"marks": [
										"key-109-na65l"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-111-oo1q8",
									"text": " (~$130) and both will sound much better than your built-in laptop mic]. If you will be doing field recordings or talking with people in situations where you don’t have your laptop, I’d consider getting a digital recorder with a USB input. I like the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-113-aiixx",
									"text": "Zoom H2N",
									"marks": [
										"key-112-zu7tl"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-114-1fb7r",
									"text": " or "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-116-4yaoi",
									"text": "H4N",
									"marks": [
										"key-115-oezhf"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-117-ifwag",
									"text": " (both very good, with a clear edge to the H4, which is what I use to record my audio)."
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-103-fw0v4",
									"href": "http://www.bluemic.com/#microphones",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-106-ku5ut",
									"href": "http://www.bluemic.com/products/snowball/",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-109-na65l",
									"href": "http://www.bluemic.com/products/yeti/",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-112-zu7tl",
									"href": "https://www.zoom-na.com/products/field-video-recording/field-recording/zoom-h2n-handy-recorder",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-115-oezhf",
									"href": "https://www.zoom-na.com/products/field-video-recording/field-recording/zoom-h4n-handy-recorder",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-123-mdjj5",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "bullet",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-119-kri52",
									"text": "Audio recording levels.",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-120-aazu9",
									"text": " This is a big deal, and it’s a little counter-intuitive, actually. The key thing here is not to record too loudly. If your audio input maxes out the extra decibels are clipped (lost) and it sounds terrible. I try to have my max peaks come in around -12 dB (you can see a little visual on your recording panel in audacity). It’s also good to try to have everyone who’s being recorded come into the mix at roughly the same volume, obviously. You can turn down your input source and adjust your overall balance in audacity or instruct people to speak up or turn their inputs down as needed.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-121-6jg8k",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_6148\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"457\"]"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-122-wtebz",
									"text": " Example of dB levels input visualization in Audacity. Peak volume represented by the end of the color bar. Green=good, yellow=watch out, red=too loud.[/caption]"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-126-puozd",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "bullet",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-124-9l62s",
									"text": "Monitoring while recording:",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-125-8tocc",
									"text": " When I record, I always wear a pair of headphones with one ear on and one off so I can hear what’s happening in the room I’m in as well as what’s happening in the call itself."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-134-o8lj4",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "bullet",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-127-8rrxp",
									"text": "Editing and post-recording production.",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-128-xt7wc",
									"text": " It’s up to you how much you want to edit stuff, obviously, but it’s really easy and addicting to do in Audacity. The biggest thing I’d recommend doing even if you don’t do any in-file editing is to normalize [bring the audio up to a desired max volume, basically] and compress the audio before exporting. Audacity has a built in compressor plug-in, and I always run it on my audio files before exporting. "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-130-ny4xz",
									"text": "Compression",
									"marks": [
										"key-129-pzebs"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-131-lb9b8",
									"text": " is super cool — what it does is reduce the absolute volume difference between your loudest and softest sounds, while still preserving the relative loudness/softness of all sounds. So the loud stuff is still louder than the quieter stuff, but within a compressed dynamic range. Normalizing can be helpful too, because it brings the loudest part of your recording right up to the max volume without clipping. This is why I recommend recording with your peaks some distance below 0 — you will never experience clipping, and your audio gets boosted to optimal levels during normalization/compression before you export. If you have questions, feel free to ask — I’m not an audio engineer, but have some interest and experience.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-132-pnk9w",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_6147\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"493\"]"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-133-03h03",
									"text": " My preferred compression settings for speech: Threshold: -18db; Noise floor: -40dB; Ratio: 4:1; Attack time: .1 sec; Decay time: .8 sec; select ‘Make up gain for 0 dB after compressing’; leave ‘Compress based on peaks’ unselected].[/caption]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-129-pzebs",
									"href": "http://www.soundonsound.com/techniques/compression-made-easy",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-137-q87q9",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "bullet",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-135-056w4",
									"text": "Export settings.",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-136-szy8g",
									"text": " I prefer to export to mp3 at 64kbps [kilobytes per second]. Because you’ll likely be doing voice only, you can choose a higher rate of compression (lower kbps in your settings). The BBC’s standard for voice only podcasts is 64kpbs, which is what we use for our podcast, but you can try it in 96 to see if the difference is audible and matters to you."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-139-h4kd9",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-138-tpby7",
									"text": "Have fun! I’m happy to be a resource as needed, especially as you get started. Making radio/podcasting is a blast, and super addictive. Can’t wait to listen what you make!"
								}
							]
						}
					]
				}
			},
			{
				"id": "posts:making-a-personal-website-a-guide-for-grad-students-and-other-academics",
				"slug": "making-a-personal-website-a-guide-for-grad-students-and-other-academics",
				"status": "published",
				"data": {
					"title": "Making a Personal Website: A guide for grad students and other academics",
					"featured_image": {
						"provider": "external",
						"id": "",
						"src": "https://steelwagstaff.info/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/15273343947_855a5a9d3a_b_network-boston-ivy-leaf.jpg"
					},
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-11-k14zb",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-0c6ep",
									"text": "I currently work as an educational technology consultant at a large Midwestern research university. Most of the people I work with are humanities/social science grad students or faculty. One of the most common questions I get asked is how to build a website. I’ve heard it so often, helped so many friends "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-3-rfm2k",
									"text": "build quick, simple websites",
									"marks": [
										"key-2-hydvo"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-4-ztibr",
									"text": " by now, and seen enough capable-yet- overwhelmed-veering-on-desperate people overpay for something that’s relatively simple to do yourself that I figured it was time to write up my advice.((The ideas for much of what I’m presenting here originated in "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-6-0byl5",
									"text": "a presentation for grad students in the environmental humanities",
									"marks": [
										"key-5-m1twa"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-7-zvh1n",
									"text": " I put together a couple of years ago along with my friend "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-9-u6s3q",
									"text": "Garrett Nelson",
									"marks": [
										"key-8-ziwym"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-10-d6ogj",
									"text": ", who is now a postdoctoral geographer at Dartmouth.))"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-2-hydvo",
									"href": "http://steelwagstaff.info/design"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-5-m1twa",
									"href": "https://docs.google.com/document/d/10Gm3HsS6TJoB19GDSa6-FY9LNx9ijS_CetM0AELfnHI/edit?usp=sharing",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-8-ziwym",
									"href": "http://people.matinic.us/garrett/#about",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-13-gu11j",
							"style": "h2",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-12-k5vah",
									"text": "What you need to make a website"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-15-wlkwj",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-14-wzo5v",
									"text": "To publish and maintain a website you will need three things:"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-19-nk28x",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "number",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-16-wb1l8",
									"text": "an address where your site lives ["
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-17-td5pn",
									"text": "domain registration",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-18-11kok",
									"text": "],"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-23-e9vds",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "number",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-20-1e0pg",
									"text": "storage space to put stuff ["
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-21-8d16c",
									"text": "web hosting",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-22-fbrlt",
									"text": "], and"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-27-03wdl",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "number",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-24-qzqgc",
									"text": "a method for writing, publishing, and editing your content ["
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-25-ux7pt",
									"text": "content management system",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-26-l9bkv",
									"text": "]."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-29-wtgze",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-28-wg0xy",
									"text": "Each of these elements can be obtained separately though one or more of them are often bundled together. Many web hosts, for example, will include one year’s worth of a domain registration in the price of creating an account, and some all-in-one content management systems (like Squarespace) will include both hosting and annual domain registration in their monthly price. I’m what follows, however, I’m going to take these three requirements in turn, describing a little more about these things commonly work and offering some recommendations. My recommendations will be biased towards low-cost, open source, DIY solutions, with privacy and ease of use as secondary considerations."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-31-j5i0q",
							"style": "h3",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-30-1om77",
									"text": "TL;DR recommendations"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-33-veuix",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-32-xfiqp",
									"text": "If all you want to know is what you should do, here’s what I’d recommend as the best choice for the greatest number of people."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-38-6e8bg",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "number",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-34-p8vem",
									"text": "Get a shared hosting account (and domain name) from "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-36-1xlvh",
									"text": "Reclaim Hosting",
									"marks": [
										"key-35-33sea"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-37-iydhd",
									"text": ". For $30 / year you can get 2GB of storage on a shared server and domain name all your own. This is all you need to build an attractive personal website."
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-35-33sea",
									"href": "https://reclaimhosting.com/shared-hosting/",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-43-8not3",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "number",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-39-wah3v",
									"text": "Install WordPress. If you use Reclaim as your host, they make this "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-41-45oo4",
									"text": "very simple",
									"marks": [
										"key-40-c552i"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-42-d42vg",
									"text": "."
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-40-c552i",
									"href": "https://portal.reclaimhosting.com/knowledgebase.php?action=displayarticle&id=2",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-54-wgylc",
							"style": "normal",
							"listItem": "number",
							"level": 1,
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-44-fy5an",
									"text": "Choose a theme((If you’re interested in the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-46-dq7x1",
									"text": "Genesis Framework",
									"marks": [
										"key-45-7qkko"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-47-epyga",
									"text": " or any of the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-49-8lpnr",
									"text": "StudioPress themes",
									"marks": [
										"key-48-fgcz4"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-50-4gw48",
									"text": ", I purchased their "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-52-mkhlb",
									"text": "Pro Plus package",
									"marks": [
										"key-51-uziid"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-53-gbvz5",
									"text": " a few years ago, which means that I’m able to install any of these themes on as many sites as I want pretty much forever. I’m happy to share. Let me know …)) and build your website."
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-45-7qkko",
									"href": "https://www.studiopress.com/features/",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-48-fgcz4",
									"href": "http://my.studiopress.com/themes/",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-51-uziid",
									"href": "http://my.studiopress.com/pro-plus/",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-72-9eam1",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-55-axx1k",
									"text": "EDIT: ",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-56-l746b",
									"text": "I’ve had some feedback on these recommendations since publishing. If you’re a Mac user who is willing to set up a GitHub account and learn to use a Command line interface, another excellent option is publish your site on GitHub pages using an excellent open source tool called "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-58-vm2ld",
									"text": "Jekyll",
									"marks": [
										"key-57-btfue"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-59-00m0u",
									"text": ". It’s totally free, and very powerful, though you will need do some slightly difficult technical things to get started. Here are two tutorials to help you get started on this route: "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-61-qioaz",
									"text": "Amanda Visconti’s guide at Programming Historian",
									"marks": [
										"key-60-5p1b2"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-62-0o067",
									"text": " and "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-64-czyrt",
									"text": "Barry Clark’s at Smashing Magazine",
									"marks": [
										"key-63-qd9a5"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-65-amh90",
									"text": ". "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-67-u19vw",
									"text": "Audrey Watters",
									"marks": [
										"key-66-ahv40"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-68-esk99",
									"text": ", one of my favorite education and technology writers, uses Jekyll to power "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-70-s6rzt",
									"text": "her site (Hack Education)",
									"marks": [
										"key-69-v61ke"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-71-5l4uu",
									"text": ", which is a good example of what you can do with the tool."
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-57-btfue",
									"href": "https://jekyllrb.com/",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-60-5p1b2",
									"href": "http://programminghistorian.org/lessons/building-static-sites-with-jekyll-github-pages",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-63-qd9a5",
									"href": "https://www.smashingmagazine.com/2014/08/build-blog-jekyll-github-pages/",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-66-ahv40",
									"href": "https://twitter.com/audreywatters",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-69-v61ke",
									"href": "http://hackeducation.com/",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-74-e0lpm",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-73-07p1q",
									"text": "So, those are my recommendations. If you’re curious to know more about the general process of building a website, however, or want to know more about any part of these recommendations, please continue on."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "break",
							"_key": "key-75-7am1x",
							"style": "lineBreak"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-77-qjdc1",
							"style": "h2",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-76-7m7gp",
									"text": "1. Obtaining an address for your website: Domain Registration"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-79-vt9hr",
							"style": "h3",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-78-v5vty",
									"text": "Brief explanation of the internet [skippable]"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-106-biv3e",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-80-g5akc",
									"text": "The internet exists as a gigantic meta-network of connected networks made up of an enormous and ever-increasing number of different nodes. Internet connected objects (like computers and other connected devices) are able to be assembled into a common network because they share a common framework for communicating (they use a protocol called "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-82-707sk",
									"text": "TCP/IP",
									"marks": [
										"key-81-6d7t7"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-83-4276i",
									"text": "). Machines and resources can be connected to the internet as clients (which request stuff) and/or servers (which respond to the requests, usually by providing what it thinks has been requested). Every device on the internet is typically issued a unique "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-85-dh7nd",
									"text": "IP number",
									"marks": [
										"key-84-ugakh"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-86-fuduj",
									"text": ", which can be used to identify and disambiguate a client or a resource connected to the network. When you use an internet browser, you usually enter a ‘web address’ and expect a website to load. What you’re typically entering in your address bar is a ‘domain name’ expressed using something called "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-87-dj3yh",
									"text": "h",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-88-51nys",
									"text": "yper"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-89-fo542",
									"text": "t",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-90-i9xi2",
									"text": "ext "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-91-fjp36",
									"text": "t",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-92-ajdgk",
									"text": "ransfer "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-93-2szjn",
									"text": "p",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-94-ncliq",
									"text": "rotocol ("
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-96-4k18x",
									"text": "http",
									"marks": [
										"key-95-advc3"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-97-fwqne",
									"text": "). Each domain name maps to a specific IP address. The IP address is the ‘real’ address of the website, and the domain name should be thought of as a more convenient, easy to remember nickname (if you’re curious to learn more, see "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-99-2h9k0",
									"text": "Paul Gil",
									"marks": [
										"key-98-r0ydb"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-100-hz0p3",
									"text": "’s very "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-102-sn75w",
									"text": "helpful explanation",
									"marks": [
										"key-101-bmjgf"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-103-k073j",
									"text": " of the difference between IP address and domain names at "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-104-jcgfe",
									"text": "Lifewire",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-105-5owjr",
									"text": ")."
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-81-6d7t7",
									"href": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-84-ugakh",
									"href": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPv6",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-95-advc3",
									"href": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypertext_Transfer_Protocol",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-98-r0ydb",
									"href": "https://twitter.com/AboutNetBasics",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-101-bmjgf",
									"href": "https://www.lifewire.com/what-is-an-ip-address-2483314",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-108-hs991",
							"style": "h3",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-107-yye7q",
									"text": "Registering a Domain Name"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-113-occyf",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-109-dbgn0",
									"text": "Because it’s incredibly difficult for individuals to buy individual IP addresses, most people who make websites start by registering a domain name (for a good primer on how domain names work, see Nikola Krajacic’s "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-111-tn7ud",
									"text": "article on the topic",
									"marks": [
										"key-110-ds837"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-112-eseal",
									"text": " at domain.me). When you register a domain name, you’ll be picking an address with two parts separated by a period — most addresses look something like this: http://example.[zzz]. When you pick the name of your website, you have the ability to making two choices: the name of your domain [the part before the period] and the top-level domain you want your site to be registered with [the part after the period]."
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-110-ds837",
									"href": "http://domain.me/how-domain-names-work/",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-115-2fdhl",
							"style": "h4",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-114-s59xx",
									"text": "Part 1: The name of your domain"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-117-34cgw",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-116-g14dq",
									"text": "When picking your domain name, you have very few constraints. The biggest one will probably be competition with other internet users. For a personal website, you may want to register a domain name that is some variant of your name. If you have a common name, you may find that your desired domain name is unavailable because someone has already registered the domain name you want. If you have an uncommon name [like mine], your choices will probably be less constrained. As a rule of thumb, shorter domain names which are easy to remember and type without misspellings are preferable to those that aren’t."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-119-98wxg",
							"style": "h4",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-118-hm4zk",
									"text": "Part 2: The Top-level domain [or TLD]"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-130-myiy1",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-120-d45wg",
									"text": "The second part of your web address will be the top-level domain of your site. Top-level domains, or TLDs, are the set of letters that follow the first period in your web address. Many TLDs (like .com or .info) can be considered open and generic, meaning anyone can register a domain name which uses them, though other common TLDs (like .edu, .gov, or .mil) are restricted to specific organization or entities. All TLDs are supposed to have descriptive significance, but these intended meanings are often unknown and frequently applied differently than their creators intended (like the popular "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-122-e8f3j",
									"text": "tech-related TLD .io",
									"marks": [
										"key-121-n1gds"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-123-zz5b7",
									"text": "). As of February 2017, there are "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-125-wlqev",
									"text": "more than 1500 available TLDs",
									"marks": [
										"key-124-x2ra9"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-126-sdeud",
									"text": ", though only the most commonly used TLDs will likely be familiar to most American internet users: .com, .org, .net, .edu, .gov, and perhaps .info or .io. The availability of so many TLD choices means that if you’re really attached to a particular domain name, you can almost certainly buy a variation on it provided that you’re willing to be flexible about the TLD. While you can use TLDs "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-128-0k55n",
									"text": "creatively",
									"marks": [
										"key-127-tkqcj"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-129-uod9h",
									"text": " [smashi.ng would be an acceptable web domain, for example, as .ng is the TLD for Nigeria], whether you’d actually want to have your website at YOURNAME.dk or some other lesser-known TLD is a different question, however."
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-121-n1gds",
									"href": "https://gigaom.com/2014/06/30/the-dark-side-of-io-how-the-u-k-is-making-web-domain-profits-from-a-shady-cold-war-land-deal/",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-124-x2ra9",
									"href": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Internet_top-level_domains",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-127-tkqcj",
									"href": "https://www.smashingmagazine.com/2009/07/get-creative-with-your-domain-names/",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-132-hu8c6",
							"style": "h4",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-131-u2kvd",
									"text": "Putting them both together"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-136-fv9vv",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-133-nm5cw",
									"text": "So, basically, what I’m saying is that you need to register a domain name for your website. The easiest way to do this is to use a domain registrar, which is a company that lets you reserve a specific domain name for a specified length of time. You rent a name, and that’s just about it. Some companies will try to upsell you a bunch of useless add-ons, which you should resist. In most cases, the only feature worth getting with your domain registration is WHOIS privacy, which allows you to shield your required registration information from marketers and other spam artists. Many registrars will even include this feature in the price of registration. Registering a domain name is not a particularly complicated process, and the service that various registrars offer is pretty much identical which means that domain registration is pretty much as close to a totally fungible commodity as you can get. And yet, the prices you’ll get charged for this can vary quite a bit. "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-134-bzq7s",
									"text": "Don’t overpay:",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-135-0tn7x",
									"text": " you should be able to register your domain for ~$10/year."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-138-6fqcp",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-137-pwb1c",
									"text": "Note that if your domain registration and your hosting are purchased with different companies (totally common), all you should need to do is make sure that your ‘name servers’ are pointed at your host. Most hosts will have very simple instructions for this, but they’ll typically need to be set to something like ‘ns1.bluehost.com’ and ‘ns2.bluehost.com.’"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-140-g3thl",
							"style": "h2",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-139-1hr9i",
									"text": "My domain registration recommendations:"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-142-rd2o1",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-141-3fb9q",
									"text": "If you’re simply building a single personal/professional website for yourself, and only need one domain, you may want to consider bundling your domain registration with your hosting (see my recommendations for shared web hosting below). If you’re going to be registering more than one domain, or plan to host with someone other than Reclaim Hosting, you should probably consider registering your domain separately from your web hosting, in part because while many hosts will give you a ‘free domain’ when you sign up for hosting, what they’re really giving you is one year of domain registration, and they’ll often charge you well above the market rate when you have to renew your registration at the end of the first year."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-144-7n6i9",
							"style": "h3",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-143-vf41l",
									"text": "For comparing prices and checking domain availability:"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-149-l7gkp",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-145-bsztk",
									"text": "Use "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-147-4xmx3",
									"text": "domcomp",
									"marks": [
										"key-146-d9a53"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-148-248zy",
									"text": ", a very simple comparison website. You enter the name you’re thinking of, and it’ll show you which TLDs are available and who’s offering what price. Look at your registrar’s going renewal price as well (since you’ll likely want to renew your registration annually) — don’t simply jump for the company offering you the lowest new registration cost. If you already have a domain registered somewhere, you should also take a look at the transfer costs — transferring domain registrations is fairly easy, and if you find a good, low-cost registrar, will save you money in the long run (I’ve transferred all my domains to NameSilo, for example)."
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-146-d9a53",
									"href": "https://www.domcomp.com/",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-152-map6y",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-150-3ae36",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_6136\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"1204\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-151-oo8q0",
									"href": "https://steelwagstaff.info/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Screen-Shot-2017-02-18-at-2.32.52-PM.png"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-153-ghrjr",
							"asset": {
