			},
			{
				"id": "posts:im-going-to-be-a-radio-dj-13-2",
				"slug": "im-going-to-be-a-radio-dj-13-2",
				"status": "published",
				"data": {
					"title": "I'm going to be a radio DJ!",
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-2-fda29",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-oqd0u",
									"text": "[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"600\"]"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-3-fuz1j",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://photos.news.wisc.edu/photos/9676/original/WSUM_studioA_09_2834.jpg?1286762458",
								"url": "http://photos.news.wisc.edu/photos/9676/original/WSUM_studioA_09_2834.jpg?1286762458"
							},
							"alt": ""
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-32-r9x3o",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-4-qqz8q",
									"text": "WSUM\"s new studio.[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-5-iuxlh",
									"text": "When I was in 6th grade, and living in Oklahoma, one of the DJs on a local radio station moved into my family's neighborhood. I think his name was something terrible, something like Jimmy Rocket. I was really pumped, especially when I'd see him pulling his car into the garage every couple of weeks. I used to think being a radio DJ would be the best job ever. And then I developed musical taste and realized how soul-crushing it would be as an adult with fully operational cognitive abilities to DJ for a commercial radio station, especially one that catered to the tastes of teenagers. So the dream sort of withered on the vine. And then when I was a senior in high school my dad bought me a subscription to "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-7-bpap6",
									"text": "CMJ",
									"marks": [
										"key-6-48y9s"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-8-gk0du",
									"text": " and I learned that there was something called "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-10-bjpmi",
									"text": "college radio",
									"marks": [
										"key-9-3fhy6"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-11-ehbm9",
									"text": ". It wasn't long before I learned there was even something called "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-13-donv7",
									"text": "pirate radio",
									"marks": [
										"key-12-cxsx5"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-14-n6jsl",
									"text": ". And the dream sent out tiny hope tendrils. And then I took a radio documentary class as an undergraduate and made a 15 minute long "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-16-qpgks",
									"text": "This American LIfe",
									"marks": [
										"key-15-wy0jg"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-17-lo6lk",
									"text": "-style piece about "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-19-lza43",
									"text": "BYU's Inernational Cinema",
									"marks": [
										"key-18-b8tnm"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-20-o67gi",
									"text": " program. It was the most fun thing I did in a college class, probably. And the dream developed a single tap root, burrowing blindly deeper and deeper. And then I came to Wisconsin and learned about WORT and WSUM. And then I learned that one of my former students, a non-traditional student who had led a a really interesting life was "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-22-e867c",
									"text": "hosting a radio show",
									"marks": [
										"key-21-p7kkx"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-23-hifyg",
									"text": " on WSUM. And then I appeared on his show as a guest ("
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-24-sq2vw",
									"text": "listen to a .mp3 of that show",
									"marks": [
										"key-21-p7kkx"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-25-fix5d",
									"text": ") to talk about "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-27-t4zyh",
									"text": "the Writers in Prisons Project",
									"marks": [
										"key-26-4f5pz"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-28-7wa8b",
									"text": " and really enjoyed being in a radio studio and seeing all the equipment and how the guts of a radio program worked.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-29-2i4rj",
									"text": "So that was it. That was as close as I got. And then I ran into that former student in the library last week ago and we talked and I mentioned how I had wanted for a long time to have a music show on the radio and how I had made plans with a colleague from grad school but he never followed through on them and we never applied for a spot and how it's something I've always wanted to do. And he said, \"well, wouldn't you know...\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-30-l03aq",
									"text": "[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-6-48y9s",
									"href": "http://www.cmj.com/"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-9-3fhy6",
									"href": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campus_radio"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-12-cxsx5",
									"href": "http://www.hobbybroadcaster.us/"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-15-wy0jg",
									"href": "http://www.thisamericanlife.org/"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-18-b8tnm",
									"href": "http://ic.byu.edu/about_us.php"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-21-p7kkx",
									"href": "http://s3.amazonaws.com/ass-jammery-archive/092+Determinism.mp3"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-26-4f5pz",
									"href": "http://writersinprisonsproject.com/index.htm"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-31-ju0k7",
									"href": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Wsum.jpg",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-33-iitio",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/0/04/Wsum.jpg",
								"url": "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/0/04/Wsum.jpg"
							},
							"alt": "WSUM"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-40-9rc09",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-34-4p2pf",
									"text": " WSUM (Photo credit: Wikipedia)[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-35-onpbe",
									"text": "And now I'm going to be DJing a weekly radio show with Pete Hnilicka every Thursday from 11AM-noon [`central time] on WSUM (91.7) in Madison starting this week!!! You can stream the show live from their "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-37-da13j",
									"text": "website",
									"marks": [
										"key-36-217hi"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-38-75yhq",
									"text": ". I'm not sure what we're going to call the show yet, but the plan is for each show to have some kind of starting theme and then proceed through a six degrees of separation kind of deal where each song connects in some way to the following song. Pete's going to primarily select more mainstream/classic rock type tunes, and I'm going to go a bit more indie and eclectic with my choice. And for our first show, this Thursday, you ask? It's starting with Stevie Wonder's \"Superstition.\" Boom.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-39-vxeim",
									"text": "[youtube=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_ul7X5js1vE]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-36-217hi",
									"href": "http://www.wsum.org/"
								}
							]
						}
					]
				}
			},
			{
				"id": "posts:william-langewiesche-on-public-grief-2",
				"slug": "william-langewiesche-on-public-grief-2",
				"status": "published",
				"data": {
					"title": "William Langewiesche on \"Public Grief\"",
					"featured_image": {
						"provider": "external",
						"id": "",
						"src": "https://steelwagstaff.info/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/16485847000_63eb59b373_z.jpg"
					},
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-3-k2kup",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-xudfl",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_336\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"220\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-2-zgy6k",
									"href": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/09/langewiesche.jpg"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-4-kgtnl",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/09/langewiesche.jpg",
								"url": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/09/langewiesche.jpg"
							},
							"alt": "photo of William Langewiesche"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-33-76tqw",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-5-8575s",
									"text": " William Langewiesche[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-6-1lic6",
									"text": "I spent some time catching up on the NPR "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-8-9qvkf",
									"text": "Story of the Day Podcast",
									"marks": [
										"key-7-vlck9"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-9-mhm3a",
									"text": " today while I was folding laundry. Some were fairly memorable, but my favorite was an interview with "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-11-3c74v",
									"text": "this ",
									"marks": [
										"key-10-gx9tx"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-12-0pllp",
									"text": "All Things Considered",
									"marks": [
										"key-10-gx9tx",
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-13-cox7c",
									"text": " interview",
									"marks": [
										"key-10-gx9tx"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-14-36myf",
									"text": " by "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-16-b89d8",
									"text": "Guy Raz",
									"marks": [
										"key-15-tzedb"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-17-lbjyy",
									"text": " with the journalist, novelist, and former pilot "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-19-am6mh",
									"text": "William",
									"marks": [
										"key-18-ydtms"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-20-dza08",
									"text": " "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-22-p5ek9",
									"text": "Langewiesche",
									"marks": [
										"key-21-6pfj4"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-23-sowuw",
									"text": ". After the World Trade Center was destroyed, Langewiesche spent five months at \"ground zero\" observing the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-25-ugmia",
									"text": "Department of Design and Construction",
									"marks": [
										"key-24-logrl"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-26-c3mkl",
									"text": "'s clean up efforts, which he detailed in a long-running series for "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-27-6i2j9",
									"text": "the Atlantic ",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-28-u636p",
									"text": "and later published as "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-30-5tjw8",
									"text": "American Ground: Unbuilding the World Trade Center",
									"marks": [
										"em",
										"key-29-bgemr"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-31-8ex0f",
									"text": ". I knew nothing about Langewiesche or this story prior to hearing the radio piece, but I was instantly impressed, especially with Langewiesche's cool and considered manner of speech, his deliberate rationality, and his insistence that his job was to observe and to speak honestly, without judgment, about the things that he observed. Despite this strong sense of journalistic integrity, I was also pleased (and somewhat surprised) to discover that there were some things he experienced that he would not write about, like the private grief of the families of the dead, he called it a \"deep, deep grief, that is everlasting.\" According to Langewiesche, he did not write about this grief because he \"think[s] that's a private matter. It would have been a violation of these people to write about their grief.\"\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-32-ugh4w",
									"text": "Later in the interview, Langewiesche said:"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-7-vlck9",
									"href": "http://www.npr.org/rss/podcast/podcast_detail.php?siteId=4819386"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-10-gx9tx",
									"href": "http://www.npr.org/2011/09/11/140363010/reporter-recalls-reckless-courage-at-ground-zero"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-15-tzedb",
									"href": "http://www.npr.org/people/6597623/guy-raz"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-18-ydtms",
									"href": "http://www.theatlantic.com/william-langewiesche/"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-21-6pfj4",
									"href": "http://www.vanityfair.com/contributors/william-langewiesche"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-24-logrl",
									"href": "http://www.nyc.gov/html/ddc/html/home/home.shtml"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-29-bgemr",
									"href": "http://us.macmillan.com/americanground"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-35-2lmv6",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-34-p2lzn",
									"text": "I believe that grief needs to be private. That doesn't mean that help can't be given to those who are grieving, it should be given. But you don't make a spectacle out of it. You don't stand up as a politician and wallow in it. And as the media, you don't wallow in it. It's not to deny the tragedy. It's to question the utility of public grief."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-37-ep53q",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-36-3mr6v",
									"text": "Hearing Langewiesche articulate his particular feelings about the events that he witnessed resonated quite powerfully with me. I too feel a certain reticence towards what feels to me like overly performed and demonstrative expressions of deep feeling and personal or private emotion. I wrote a few days ago about seeking to avoid the spectacle of 9/11 commemoration (I think Newt Gingrich even referred to 9/11 10 year anniversary \"celebrations\" in the Republican Presidential Primary debate last week), and why I have had a certain distaste and aversion to media representations of the disaster. After hearing Langewiesche speak about his experiences, I'd like to reaffirm his reminder that we ought \"to question the utility of public grief.\""
								}
							]
						}
					]
				}
			},
			{
				"id": "posts:the-weeks-best-reads-feb-19-2015",
				"slug": "the-weeks-best-reads-feb-19-2015",
				"status": "draft",
				"data": {
					"title": "The Week's Best Reads [Feb 19, 2015]",
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-6-30rum",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-i0xap",
									"text": "I read a lot. When I'm on the bus, when I'm traveling, when I'm hanging out with a sleeping baby, when I've got a few minutes spare, whenever. I still read print books, but because I do a lot of my reading in low-light situations, lately I've been reading more and more in my iPad.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-2-od81e",
									"text": "For that, I've been using a combination of feedly (as my rss feed reader), Pocket (as my collector of longer pieces), and iBooks (for eBooks) and Adobe Reader (for PDFs) to read. I've realized that I read a lot of stuff from around the web--mostly long form journalism--and want to have a place where I keep track of it and share it out both for others and for myself.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-3-xfvw3",
									"text": "So I'm going to try something new here. Each week, on Sunday evening, I'll post a list of the best things I read during the previous week.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-4-j50ob",
									"text": "Here's my first list:\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-5-i0g1t",
									"text": " "
								}
							]
						}
					]
				}
			},
			{
				"id": "posts:favorite-passages-jonathan-wilsons-inverting-pyramid-2",
				"slug": "favorite-passages-jonathan-wilsons-inverting-pyramid-2",
				"status": "published",
				"data": {
					"title": "Favorite Passages from Jonathan Wilson's Inverting the Pyramid",
					"featured_image": {
						"provider": "external",
						"id": "",
						"src": "https://steelwagstaff.info/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/pyramid.jpg"
					},
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-13-y2zpt",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-je4i5",
									"text": "In the past several years, I've become a full-fledged soccer fan. I've always followed (and played) sports, switching over the years from an interest in baseball to football to basketball and most recently, to soccer. It's now the sport that I follow most closely, play most regularly for recreation, and read and think about most often. Over the past couple of years I've become a regular reader of a few soccer journalists that I think are generally quite outstanding, among whom my favorites lately have been "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-3-961aa",
									"text": "Brian Phillips",
									"marks": [
										"key-2-ixzz5"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-4-tiyc6",
									"text": ", who's just a gorgeous, intelligent, thoughtful writer and "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-6-1ck7t",
									"text": "Michael Cox",
									"marks": [
										"key-5-x9am7"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-7-fcscx",
									"text": ", who's really helped me to understand the tactical nuances of the game and develop an appreciation for some of global football's more subtle playmakers and geniuses. I think I saw the book referenced a few times by Cox (or perhaps it was "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-9-h8wnv",
									"text": "Simon Kuper",
									"marks": [
										"key-8-9f8qb"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-10-6cmk7",
									"text": "?), but I recently decided it was time for me to read "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-11-xf7ox",
									"text": "Inverting the Pyramid",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-12-glbdn",
									"text": ", Jonathan Wilson's well-regarded history of soccer tactics. I just finished it. It was excellent, and in what follows, I'll present some of my favorite passages:"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-2-ixzz5",
									"href": "http://www.runofplay.com/brian-phillips/",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-5-x9am7",
									"href": "http://www.zonalmarking.net/",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-8-9f8qb",
									"href": "http://www.ft.com/intl/life-arts/simon-kuper",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-15-gms3k",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-14-5eo62",
									"text": "The first match in Austria took place on November 15, 1894 between the Vienna Cricket Club and gardeners from Baron Rothschild’s estate, but local interest was so great that by 1911 the cricket club had become Wiener Amateure."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-17-bf8sp",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-16-w6v1a",
									"text": "There's so much to love in this passage from the beginning of Chapter 2, but how can you not swoon over these two facts: The first soccer match played in Austria was contested by the Baron Rothschild's gardeners! Even better, local interest in soccer was so great there that amateur wieners were born! If I ever adopt an Austrian club (or need a name for an intramural team), it will be Wiener Amateure for sure."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-19-idydy",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-18-3y9lq",
									"text": "Arsenal won the league in 1931 and 1944 and were beaten in the 1932 Cup final only by a highly controversial goal. [Brian] Glanville wrote of them \"approaching the precision of a machine,\" and, in their rapid transition from defense to attack, the unfussy functionalism of their style, there was a sensibility in keeping with the art deco surroundings of Highbury. The machine analogy is telling, recalling as it does Le Corbusier's reference to a house as \"a machine for living in\"; this was modernist soccer. William Carlos Williams, similarly, in a phrase that would become almost a slogan for his version of modernism, described a poem as \"a machine made of words ... there can be no part, as in any other machine, that is redundant.\" Chapman's Arsenal were very much of their age. \"It was,\" Joy said of their style, \"twentieth-century, terse, exciting, spectacular, economic, devastating.\""
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-22-9cqfr",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-20-orhkr",
									"text": "Stuck in my mind because I've written about Williams' machine poetics as part of my own academic research. Nice to see this cultural cross-pollination from Wilson.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-21-7wpjk",
									"text": "The lengthy section on Béla Guttmann in Chapter 6 was extraordinary (the original wandering coach, a proto-Larry Brown). Here are some of the most impressive details:"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-27-b8ygx",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-23-ebvgh",
									"text": "Whenever he was asked how he survived the war, Guttman [a Hungarian Jew] would always reply, \"God helped me.\" His elder brother died in a concentration camp, and it seems probable that contacts from Hakoah [a Viennese football club] helped him escape to Switzerland, where he was interned. It was certainly there that Guttmann met his wife, but he refused always to speak of his wartime experiences, and his autobiography, published in 1964, contains a single paragraph on the subject: \"In the last fifteen years countless books have been written about the destructive years of struggle for life and death. It would thus be superfluous to trouble our readers with such details.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-24-7z0j5",
									"text": "By 1945, he was back in Hungary with Vasas, and the following spring he moved on to Romania with Ciocanul, where he insisted on being paid in edible goods so as to circumvent the food shortages and inflation afflicting most of Europe at the time. His departure was characteristic. When a director sought to interfere with team selection, Guttmann apparently turned to him, said, \"OK, you run the club; you seem to have the basics,\" and left.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-25-8ttff",
									"text": "... Guttmann, who was adamant that soccer should be played the \"right way,\" had spent the first half trying to calm the aggressive approach of the fullback Mihály Patyi. Furious with him, Guttman instructed Patyi not to go out for the second half, even though that would leave Kispest down to ten men. Puskás told the defender to stay on. Patyi vacillated and eventually ignored his manager, at which Guttmann retired to the stands for the second half, most of which he spent reading a racing paper, then took a tram home and never returned.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-26-jjqtl",
									"text": "... On he wandered ... midway through the 1953-1954 season, to AC Milan. He lifted them to third in that first season and had them top of the table when he was dismissed nineteen games into 1954-1955 following a series of disputes with the board. \"I have been sacked,\" he told a stunned press conference convened to announce his departure, \"even though I am neither a criminal nor a homosexual. Goodbye.\" From then on he insisted on a clause in his contracts stipulating he couldn't be dismissed while his team was at the top of the league."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-29-x9l15",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-28-d0bio",
									"text": "Wow. Just wow. Another great section was the chapter which looked at Lobanovskyi's technological optimism and scientific approach to soccer:"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-35-a1oo7",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-30-6k72z",
									"text": "Soccer, he explained, eventallly became for him a system of twenty-two elements--two subsystems of eleven elements--moving within a define area (the field) and subject to a series of restrictions (the laws of the game). If the two subsystems were equal, the outcome would be a draw. If one was stronger, it would win.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-31-qrnj3",
									"text": "... The aspect that Lobanovskyi found truly fascinating is that the subsystems were subject to a peculiarity: the efficiency of the subsystem is greater than the sum of the efficiencies of the elements that compose it. ... Soccer, he concluded, was less about individuals than about coalitions and the connections among them. \"All life,\" as he later said, \"is a number.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-32-i4otv",
									"text": "... [from his autobiography, "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-33-l77v5",
									"text": "Endless Match",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-34-h50hz",
									"text": "] \"It is impossible to rely on luck or on accidents in modern football. It is necessary to create the ensemble, a collective of believers who subordinate themselves to the common playing idea.\""
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-37-fauz0",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-36-t97do",
									"text": "Terrifying, and brutally efficient, Lobanovskyi's remarks bear for me so many of the hallmarks of totalitarian, ideological thinking. One of the book's most beautiful and lyrical passages, was also dedicated to a Ukrainian, but one of a decidedly different bent: Alexander Prokopenko, whose \"lifestyle,\" Wilson claims, \"would have disbarred him from getting anywhere near a Lobanovskyi side\":"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-42-yeuos",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-38-iw7sq",
									"text": "He was a heartbreak of a midfielder, a genius whose talent was an unbridled as his capacity for alcohol. A painfully shy man, he was so tormented by a speech impediment that he refused ever to be interviewed. It didn't matter: Dinamo fans knew what he thought because he drank with them. More than that, he was one of them, just another worker from Minsk who happened to be a superb instinctive soccer player and an industrious one at that. \"The tribune knew he would go for ninety minutes,\" the journalist Vasily Sarychev wrote in "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-39-myqo4",
									"text": "The Moment and the Destiny",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-40-2bmp3",
									"text": ", his book celebrating Belarus's top sportsmen. \"He would sooner die than cease his motion on the pitch through tiredness or laziness.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-41-gy9vt",
									"text": "... He was readmitted to the LTP [a state-sponsored rehab clinic] in 1989 but died two months later, aged just thirty-five. \"He was followed by the smell of grass and of skin, by the joy of his goals and by empty cans,\" Sarychev wrote. \"When the need for football went, the urge died in him, the urge he was born to fulfil.\""
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-47-pxewa",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-43-nrr1p",
									"text": "Another delightful character Wilson's book introduced me to was Miroslav \"Ćiro\" Blažević, an irrepressible Bosnian Croat, famous for his development of the 3-5-2 formation in the 1980s and 90s. Wilson relates this wonderful story narrated by Blažević about the Croatian national team's preparation for their "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-45-ryzmx",
									"text": "1998 World Cup quarterfinal match against Germany",
									"marks": [
										"key-44-ilplp"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-46-z2ddl",
									"text": ":"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-44-ilplp",
									"href": "http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/matches/world-cup/match=8783/",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-52-d0y0y",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-48-85efr",
									"text": "I spend the whole night thinking about theory. I had a problem with [Oliver] Bierhoff, because I didn't have a skilled player who could beat him in the air, so I had the idea of stopping the crosses coming in. I was thinking about telling the players the story about Rommel and Montgomery. Rommel was much, much better in strategy, but he didn't have fuel. So the tanks couldn't move and Montgomery wins.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-49-mmm1r",
									"text": "Then that morning, the guy who was with me said [the Croatia president Franjo] Tudjman was calling, and Tudjman said 'Ciro, you must win'. I was on my way to the dressing room with my theories, and there are a lot of mirrors in every dressing room. I looked at myself in the mirror and I was a kind of green colour. So I thought 'Oh my God, am I going to die?'\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-50-dkwd8",
									"text": "I went to the room where the players were waiting for me – Šuker, Boban, Bokšić ... and I had everything drawn on my paper, but I didn't start to talk about anything. I couldn't, because I was thinking was I going to die or not? I was looking at the players and there was silence in the dressing room, and after a few moments I saw that they were the same green colour as me.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-51-d8jg3",
									"text": "\"My theory was seven or eight minutes long, and I knew I wouldn't be able to keep their attention so long. I didn't start to talk about my theory. They were more and more green. So I crumpled my theories and threw them down, and after seven minutes I had said nothing about them. Fuck the theory. So I just said, 'you have to go outside and die today for the Croatian flag and all the people who have given their lives'. No dealing with Bierhoff, nothing. And we won 3-0. You have to understand the psychology of the players. You have to have that sort of relationship with the team, so you can communicate your state of soul."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-54-szocc",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-53-hdvpk",
									"text": "A glorious story, wonderfully told. 'Fuck the theory,' indeed. On the subject of locker room talks, Wilson also includes this morsel about Manchester United's current dictator-manager Louis van Gaal's behavior while serving as Bayern Munich's manager:"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-56-1x5kc",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-55-llocd",
									"text": "[H]e made the point that he was unafraid of his big-name players by dropping his trousers in the dressing-room. \"The coach wanted to make clear to us that he can leave out any player, it was all the same to him because, as he said, he had the balls,\" said the forward Luca Toni. \"He demonstrated this literally. I have never experienced anything like it, it was totally crazy. Luckily I didn't see a lot, because I wasn't in the front row.\""
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-58-hkui6",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-57-xpi6p",
									"text": "Again, 'van Gaal's Front Row' or better yet 'van Gaal's Got Balls' would make an excellent intramural team name, or Manchester United fanzine title. So van Gaal is made of iron, and is an insane tyrant. Not incredibly surprising, particularly if you listened to him take all the credit for everything positive the Dutch did in the last World Cup. In contrast with the indisputably successful van Gaal, one my favorite profiles in the book, however, was Wilson's treatment of the idealistic, some would even say romantic, visionary Marco Bielsa, who has had an enormous influence on the modern game, despite winning almost nothing as a manager since the 2004 Olympics. Here's a lovely Bielsa story about his response to losing a 1991 Copa Libertadores tie at home by a scoreline of 6-0:"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-61-o8d7h",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-59-bomds",
									"text": "Bielsa was distraught. The team went on to Santa Fe for that weekend's league game against Unión, and it was there, in the Hotel Conquistador, that something extraordinary happened. \"I shut myself in my room, turned off the light, closed the curtains and I realised the true meaning of an expression we sometimes use lightly: 'I want to die.' I burst into tears. I could not understand what was happening around me. I suffered as a professional and I suffered as a fan.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-60-fzbcf",
									"text": "He phoned his wife, Laura, \"and presented an argument that for many would be irrefutable: 'For three months our daughter was held between life and death. Not she is fine. Does it make any sense that I want the earth to swallow me over the result of a football match?' The reasoning was brilliant but, nonetheless, my suffering from what had happened demanded immediate vindication.\""
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-63-2lljr",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-62-0dub7",
									"text": "The final passage that struck me as particularly memorable were a pair of quotations, one from the colorful Argentinian manager César Luis Menotti, and the other from Bielsa. Menotti's argument is:"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-65-gdqoa",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-64-6dk1l",
									"text": "There's a right-wing football and a left-wing football. Right-wing football wants to suggest that life is struggle. It demands sacrifices. We have to become of steel and win by any method ... obey and function, that's what those with power want from the players. That's how they create retards, useful idiots that go with the system."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-67-yp6wp",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-66-5h9s2",
									"text": "Here's Bielsa on the same subject:"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-69-5zlww",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-68-f2118",
									"text": "Totally mechanised teams are useless, because they get lost when they lose their script. But I don't like either ones that live only on the inspiration of their soloists, because when God doesn't turn them on, they are left totally at the mercy of their opponents."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-71-kqmiz",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-70-nvd9c",
									"text": "That's just a taste of the book, but hopefully enough to convince you that's it's well worth a read. The edition I read had been updated through the rise and fall of Guardiola's Barcelona teams, and featured an epilogue reflecting on Bayern Munich's 2013 Champions League victory, so the book felt very recent and relevant for the contemporary moment. A very impressive, very enlightening work, and highly recommended for anyone interested in a historical, tactical, or generally more thoughtful appreciation of the beautiful game."
								}
							]
						}
					]
				}
			},
			{
				"id": "posts:expressing-gratitude",
				"slug": "expressing-gratitude",
				"status": "published",
				"data": {
					"title": "Expressing Gratitude",
					"featured_image": {
						"provider": "external",
						"id": "",
						"src": "https://steelwagstaff.info/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/thisisnotaboutwesz.jpg"
					},
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-6-05yg1",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-p7zn5",
									"text": "In 1934, when George Oppen was 26 years old, he published "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-2-auxes",
									"text": "Discrete Series",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-3-v0qr0",
									"text": ", a volume of his poetry. It included a preface from Ezra Pound, then living in Rapallo, Italy, which ended with these lines: \"I salute a serious craftsman, a sensibility which is not every man’s sensibility and which has not been got out of any other man’s books.\" It was accurate in many ways, emphasizing Oppen's carefully cultivated identity as a craftsman, a skilled laborer and mechanic, even as it contained a slight dig at Oppen's own lack of erudition or learning. Shortly after its publication, George and his wife Mary would abandon poetry for many years, joining the Communist Party and becoming active organizers in several Popular Front efforts around labor, housing, and relief in New York City.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-4-reb4z",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_1759\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"470\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-5-gkrmz",
									"href": "http://steelwagstaff.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/18/2013/10/oppens.jpg"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-7-ft1gd",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://steelwagstaff.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/18/2013/10/oppens.jpg?w=470",
								"url": "http://steelwagstaff.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/18/2013/10/oppens.jpg?w=470"
							},
							"alt": "George and Mary Oppen"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-19-st22v",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-8-c2ti7",
									"text": " George and Mary Oppen[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-9-19f18",
									"text": "It would be roughly 25 years before George Oppen would return to writing poems, and almost 30 before he published another book of poems, his "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-10-zui6w",
									"text": "The Materials",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-11-a2rql",
									"text": ", published in 1962 by New Directions Press (with the support of his sister "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-13-fu1t5",
									"text": "June Degnan Oppen",
									"marks": [
										"key-12-hyzgq"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-14-34wfu",
									"text": ", who was then the publisher of the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-15-e9od9",
									"text": "San Francisco Review",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-16-w4unx",
									"text": ").\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-17-e0ksj",
									"text": "[caption id=\"\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-12-hyzgq",
									"href": "http://socialarchive.iath.virginia.edu/xtf/view?docId=degnan-june-oppen-cr.xml"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-18-de1kz",
									"href": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:EzraPound_Passport.png",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-20-3zx2h",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/65/EzraPound_Passport.png/300px-EzraPound_Passport.png",
								"url": "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/65/EzraPound_Passport.png/300px-EzraPound_Passport.png"
							},
							"alt": "Ezra Pound United States Passport marked canceled."
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-25-msi3l",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-21-vkwq3",
									"text": " Ezra Pound United States Passport marked canceled. (Photo credit: Wikipedia)[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-22-vy9ns",
									"text": "That same year, Oppen sent a copy of "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-23-06inx",
									"text": "The Materials ",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-24-k8sv7",
									"text": "along with this letter to Ezra Pound, who was then living in Italy and suffering from fairly severe depression after the failure of European fascism, his own arrest for treason and subsequent 12-year incarceration in St. Elizabeth's Hospital, a federally run psychiatric facility in Washington, D.C.:"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-31-afepz",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-26-i1u1t",
									"text": "Dear Pound,\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-27-kk1vo",
									"text": "You'll see that the back cover of this book quotes an introduction you wrote for my poems many years ago. I was in fact about twenty-one.\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-28-99lqp",
									"text": "I suppose if we should take to talking politics to each other I would disagree even more actively than all those others who have disagreed, but there has been no one living during my life time who has been as generous or as pure as you toward literature and toward writers. Nor anyone less generously thanked.\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-29-knwdt",
									"text": "I know of no one who does not owe you a debt.\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-30-xxnhc",
									"text": "George Oppen"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-33-h9ea8",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-32-mtt9o",
									"text": "As this letter may in part make clear, Oppen had complex and ambivalent feelings about Pound. He and Mary certainly disagreed with (perhaps even hated?) his politics, and among the scraps of paper Oppen had in his working space at the time of his death was this note, pinned above his writing desk:"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-38-zjqsn",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-34-6l2xj",
									"text": "A Note to Pound in heaven:\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-35-hehzl",
									"text": "Only one mistake, Ezra!\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-36-981ze",
									"text": "You should have talked\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-37-p8kfd",
									"text": "to women."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-42-k729y",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-39-ua9bd",
									"text": "What for me is remarkable about all of this is what seems to be Oppen's extraordinary kindness. Certainly there was respect for Pound, the man and the poet, and they had their own personal history. But it seems to me that Oppen did not have to write to Pound, nor acknowledge his own debt to Pound's extraordinary personal generosity, nor omit Pound's ferocious anti-semitism or monstrous politics (of which Oppen was certainly aware). But he did, and with what I think is wonderful grace and great magnanimity. In 1980, just a few years before he died, and in the period where Oppen was suffering from the Alzheimer's which would ultimately claim his life, he tells Burton Hatlen and Tom Mandel this story, of his and Mary's going to meet Pound in James Laughlin's (the publisher of "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-40-bxjd6",
									"text": "New Directions",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-41-8hd5i",
									"text": ") office:"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-54-58aqt",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-43-yt35x",
									"text": "GO: We wept on each other in the New Directions office, that's what happened.\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-44-qvrpr",
									"text": "MO: In 1969.\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-45-wssw4",
									"text": "GO: And I don't know how sincere he was or wasn't. That was when Pound came out of St. Elizabeth's and Jay Laughlin had arranged small groups to talk to Pound. Everyone was somewhat afraid that-\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-46-7s1lm",
									"text": "MO: We met in Jay's office.\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-47-cgyac",
									"text": "GO: We met in Jay's office-that was our little group-he wanted to keep the groups small so that the news shouldn't break out that Pound was roaming around free or anything of that sort that might make waves. And we were waiting for Pound to come in and ah, making chatter and finally Pound arrived with Olga and sat absolutely dead silent and everybody became nervous and started chattering and Jay had a moment of inspiration and said, \"Ezra, show George your new book.\" And Pound in a sepulchral voice said, How do I know he wants it?\" You understand well enough what that means. So I stood up and walked over to him and held my hand out and said, \"I want it\" -a very dramatic thing-and Pound stood up and once he stood he was very close to me. We were in fact touching, and Pound began to weep, so I wept. So we went home. Neither of us could speak, so we went home, and it's impossible to understand-\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-48-p5xo0",
									"text": "MO: That book?\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-49-a11sh",
									"text": "GO: No, to understand Pound.\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-50-8xdo4",
									"text": "MO: But that book [Drafts & Fragments of Cantos CX-CXVII, 1968] also had the blacked-out phrases and so on that Jay would not print-the unspeakable and anti-Semitic-\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-51-w4qv6",
									"text": "GO: I think Pound in fact was caught in the idea of being "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-52-467gp",
									"text": "macho",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-53-uswd4",
									"text": ", though the word didn't exist at that time. He was going to be the pounding poet, the masculine poet."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-59-7ooyh",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-55-gwxy0",
									"text": "There is obviously great pathos in this story, and some wry irony, humor, and self-deprecation (Oppen's description of his actions as \"a very dramatic thing\" is not to be read as virtuous, if you understand Oppen), but what moves me is the way that this story plays out as a series of embodied gesture. Oppen stands up and walks over and holds his hand out and Pound stands up and the two of them are touching and Pound begins to weep, so George Oppen weeps, and neither of them "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-56-afiwq",
									"text": "could",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-57-xwroz",
									"text": " speak, and then they go home. Perhaps some might read this story as a failure of masculine communicativity, but that's not how I choose to read it, and I don't think that's how Oppen chose to interpret it, either.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-58-vl75y",
									"text": "All this to say that I want to be generous in this way, even to those whose ideas and speech I find hateful, to return generosity for generosity, and to see other beings in their full complexity, wherever I can. I want to enact the embodied gestures which show clearly that I want to receive the work and gifts of others and which unlock the possibility of remorse and reconciliation, even if poorly articulated. And I am grateful to the letters of George Oppen for what I see of these lessons there."
								}
							]
						}
					]
				}
			},
			{
				"id": "posts:how-to-write-a-letter-to-the-editor",
				"slug": "how-to-write-a-letter-to-the-editor",
				"status": "published",
				"data": {
					"title": "How to Write a Letter to the Editor",
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-16-3vxin",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-hzaia",
									"text": "I know I keep writing about Oppen and his letters, but I just can't help it. Today I was typing up my notes from his mid-60s letters, and remembered a pretty tremendous letter he wrote to "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-3-pg5ym",
									"text": "Lita Hornick",
									"marks": [
										"key-2-zryst"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-4-lzjwe",
									"text": ", then the managing editor of "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-5-tlo8i",
									"text": "Kulchur,",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-6-r1pum",
									"text": " in response to "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-7-qgtga",
									"text": "Kulchur",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-8-wocs8",
									"text": "'s decision to print \"Soirées,\" a Felix Pollak poem he wrote lampooning Denise Levertov's \""
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-10-ajoh4",
									"text": "Matins",
									"marks": [
										"key-9-3ym8q"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-11-dw51w",
									"text": ".\" Levertov was, at the time, the poetry editor of "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-12-m0izl",
									"text": "The Nation",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-13-7ncyn",
									"text": ".\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-14-lbff0",
									"text": "[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"768\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-2-zryst",
									"href": "http://www.columbia.edu/cu/lweb/archival/collections/ldpd_4078552/index.html"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-9-3ym8q",
									"href": "http://www.poetryfoundation.org/poetrymagazine/poem/18025"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-15-2hks9",
									"href": "http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Denise-levertov.jpg",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-17-myhrz",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/99/Denise-levertov.jpg",
								"url": "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/99/Denise-levertov.jpg"
							},
							"alt": "Portriat of Denise Levertov"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-26-m7azw",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-18-1tog5",
									"text": " Portriat of Denise Levertov (Photo credit: Wikipedia)[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-19-kf1f9",
									"text": "I was particularly interested in this little literary spat because I've been a curator for the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-21-qypp4",
									"text": "FELIX reading series",
									"marks": [
										"key-20-6n21k"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-22-ewk9p",
									"text": " I hadn't read Pollak's poem, and I wanted to see what the fuss was all about, so I went to Special Collections in the UW-Madison library, dug up the issue of "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-23-9cyv9",
									"text": "Kulchur ",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-24-w5tx7",
									"text": "(Vol. 18, summer 1965) it appeared in.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-25-v7z4f",
									"text": "[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"669\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-20-6n21k",
									"href": "http://felixreadingseries.wordpress.com/about/"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-27-01bwz",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://cdn.realitystudio.org/images/bibliographic_bunker/kulchur/kulchur.18.jpg",
								"url": "http://cdn.realitystudio.org/images/bibliographic_bunker/kulchur/kulchur.18.jpg"
							},
							"alt": "Cover of Kulchur 18"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-32-xtwqs",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-28-2tila",
									"text": "Cover of Kulchur 18 (Summer 1965)[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-29-x8sbr",
									"text": "I've scanned and included Pollak's poem below:\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-30-wx0fz",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_245\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"604\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-31-uwoe0",
									"href": "http://felixreadingseries.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/pollak_page_1.jpg"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-33-5842k",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://felixreadingseries.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/pollak_page_1.jpg",
								"url": "http://felixreadingseries.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/pollak_page_1.jpg"
							},
							"alt": ""
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-37-4evnh",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-34-d12gk",
									"text": " The first half of Felix Pollak's \"Soirées\"[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-35-gtv1t",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_246\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"604\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-36-bc2ak",
									"href": "http://felixreadingseries.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/pollak_page_2.jpg"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-38-sdwl1",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://felixreadingseries.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/pollak_page_2.jpg",
								"url": "http://felixreadingseries.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/pollak_page_2.jpg"
							},
							"alt": ""
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-45-nlijz",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-39-p1y5v",
									"text": " The second half of Felix Pollak's \"Soirées.\" Sorry about my fingertips on the left there.[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-40-lcwyx",
									"text": "Pollak claims in his footnote that he has \"neither a person nor an impersonal grudge or grievance against Miss Levertov,\" and then attempts to place the onus of responsibility onto Levertov--almost as if he believed he could bully her into publishing his work, writing that \"a breathlessly waiting world will be able to judge ... if Miss Levertov could take the above in the spirit in which it was dished out: the spirit of good dirty fun\" by whether or not Levertov chose to publish in some future issue of "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-41-89iba",
									"text": "The Nation",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-42-7hz8y",
									"text": ". Others may read this differently, but my impression of Pollak's behavior in this interaction is that of a rather cruel and dull bully, one who I suspect may have felt particularly spurned by having his poetry rejected for publication in "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-43-qk6z8",
									"text": "The Nation ",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-44-6yrbh",
									"text": "by Levertov, though I understand that his personality had far more nuance and range in other settings. In any case, here's Oppen's letter to Hornick, the woman who decided to publish Pollak's poem:"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-52-y4o4i",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-46-jffxt",
									"text": "Dear Lita:\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-47-75cr7",
									"text": "I'd like to suggest to you that if Kulchur prints such things as Felix Pollack's attack on Denise Levertov, the magazine will become an instrument for the blackmail of editors. I would like most seriously to suggest to you that it is within the province of an editor to prevent that use of a magazine. Moreover I think that "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-48-nkbm1",
									"text": "kind",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-49-lu277",
									"text": " of attack on a woman poet -- deliberately speaking of shit, menstruation, wet dreams, falsies -- is obviously injurious to poetry, to the freedom of poetry, an attempt to destroy a poet, tho of course it will not do so.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-50-suzz4",
									"text": "I recognize that this is very much in the tone of a letter to a local newspaper; I mean it in approximately that spirit. I think the piece is unforgivable, not so much to have written -- it is common to be very angry at editors who refuse a poem -- as to have printed. I think really, really, really, whatever one's debt to the poor, the unknown, the furious, I think one need not print such things. And I write to tell you so.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-51-lu941",
									"text": "With regards, tho, of course,"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-68-8icpm",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-53-qammo",
									"text": "Rachel Blau Du Plessis, the editor of Oppen's selected letters, writes in her notes on this letter that when she read this letter to George and Mary in May of 1982, George's response was: \"Let's send it again.\"  Assuming that dementia had destroyed much of Oppen's faculties at this time, in this case the impulse seems both wonderfully sharp and possessed of a crucial lucidity.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-54-faqq9",
									"text": "I can't remember exactly when I became aware of the practice, but at some point in my life I learned that my for any purchase over $100, my parents had a rule that they always needed to sleep on the decision for at least a day--that way they'd avoid rash impulse buys and be more careful and prudent in their spending. I'm very much my parents' child in this regard, and try to practice the same thing in regard to my own spending habits. I wonder whether a similar rule might not be helpful in regard to the words we publish, commit to print, or otherwise make public? Oppen's remark that \"whatever one's debt to the poor, the unknown, the furious, I think one need not print such things\" seems so accurate and so precise to me for many of the same reasons that I often feel embarrassed to read my teenage journals--the ephemerality of sentiment combined with the failure of impulse control in these situations does not produce the kind of expression that I feel worth dignifying or preserving through poetry.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-55-nhago",
									"text": "In some respects, the ubiquity of social media and personally-branded expressive digital publishing platforms seems to have moved petulance and public expressions of idiocy, cruelty, or snap judgments into a particularly important role in contemporary culture. Witness the rise of sites like "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-57-epq2e",
									"text": "Undetweetable",
									"marks": [
										"key-56-arngy"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-58-ck0x1",
									"text": " and "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-60-q3wqh",
									"text": "Politwhoops",
									"marks": [
										"key-59-0zwk4"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-61-wnn8q",
									"text": " and the way that the web economy's drive for page views had "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-63-0o9gz",
									"text": "Gawkerized news content",
									"marks": [
										"key-62-e9a3p"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-64-vp7q1",
									"text": " and "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-66-0e5zt",
									"text": "journalistic standards",
									"marks": [
										"key-65-gh0yy"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-67-41qfi",
									"text": ". I suppose what I'm saying is not that there is no place for \"first thought, best thought\" philosophies, or for content produced to drive up page counts. Certainly, there are many editors who would defend Hornick's decision to publish Pollak's decision as shrewd business--it lampooned a semi-famous figure, it titillated and perhaps delighted some of its readers, it prominently featured sex and excretion, and it perhaps even generated a bit of buzz, some conversation. Fair points, I suppose. It's just that for me, poetry does (and should do, ought to do, even must do) something else. Poetry editors can (and do) publish whatever they like for whatever reasons (no matter how whimsical, haphazard, or even capricious they may be) the want, all fine and true. That doesn't mean that we must respect them or their editorial judgments. As for me, I'm going to start drafting letters to editors--both appreciative and otherwise--but I won't send them until I've slept on them for at least one night."
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-56-arngy",
									"href": "http://undetweetable.com/"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-59-0zwk4",
									"href": "http://politwoops.sunlightfoundation.com/"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-62-e9a3p",
									"href": "http://www.niemanlab.org/2012/03/i-cant-stop-reading-this-analysis-of-gawkers-editorial-strategy/"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-65-gh0yy",
									"href": "http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2011/04/learning-to-love-the-shallow-divisive-unreliable-new-media/8415/2/?single_page=true"
								}
							]
						}
					]
				}
			},
			{
				"id": "posts:how-to-write-a-dare-letter",
				"slug": "how-to-write-a-dare-letter",
				"status": "published",
				"data": {
					"title": "How To Write a \"DARE\" Letter",
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-3-2cwvz",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-kqwfh",
									"text": "[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"200\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-2-ub41f",
									"href": "http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:L.N.Tolstoy_Prokudin-Gorsky.jpg",
									"blank": true
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-4-7nn5p",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c6/L.N.Tolstoy_Prokudin-Gorsky.jpg",
								"url": "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c6/L.N.Tolstoy_Prokudin-Gorsky.jpg"
							},
							"alt": "&quot;Lev Tolstoy in Yasnaya Polyana&quot;, 19..."
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-29-8v83r",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-5-28719",
									"text": " Anti-drug crusader \"Lev Tolstoy in Yasnaya Polyana\", 1908, the first color photo portrait in Russia (Photo credit: Wikipedia)[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-6-ajtuw",
									"text": "So there are "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-8-kbbmp",
									"text": "\"kids, don't do drugs\" lectures",
									"marks": [
										"key-7-n5jqz"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-9-rnegs",
									"text": ", and then there are "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-11-1qr2j",
									"text": "\"kids, don't do drugs\" lectures",
									"marks": [
										"key-10-v9m9g"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-12-brk38",
									"text": " (like Tolstoy's "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-14-45g1k",
									"text": "\"Why Do Men Stupefy Themselves\"",
									"marks": [
										"key-13-tksly"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-15-sfcc9",
									"text": "--an absolute classic).\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-16-am2tm",
									"text": "I grew up Mormon, which meant that the Word of Wisdom ("
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-18-1nfu8",
									"text": "Section 89",
									"marks": [
										"key-17-zhlfl"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-19-uz3as",
									"text": " of the Doctrine and Covenants, a book of LDS scripture) formed the bedrock of my attitude towards 'mind-altering' substances. While I'm no longer strictly observant, I've still never smoked (anything!) or even tasted coffee, and never have developed a special taste for any kind of alcohol--a sip of wine's alright, I guess, but doesn't knock my socks off.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-20-g438n",
									"text": "Well, I "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-22-m73g4",
									"text": "wrote recently",
									"marks": [
										"key-21-jqnnt"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-23-ek907",
									"text": " about finishing George Oppen's "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-24-x8qyx",
									"text": "Selected Letters",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-25-m6f2a",
									"text": ". This past week, I've been going back through the book, typing up my notes on the letters and organizing the extracts that I think will be of use in my dissertation. Just today I re-read a letter from Oppen to his niece Aubrey Degnan-Sutter (probably written in October 1964) that is probably one of the best \""
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-27-4qnt8",
									"text": "kids, don't do drugs",
									"marks": [
										"key-26-f5hy6"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-28-v7qqx",
									"text": "\" messages I've ever read."
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-7-n5jqz",
									"href": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-iYY2FQHFwE",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-10-v9m9g",
									"href": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HB-Kkvf5j5Y",
									"blank": true
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-13-tksly",
									"href": "http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Why_Do_Men_Stupefy_Themselves%3F"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-17-zhlfl",
									"href": "http://www.lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/89?lang=eng"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-21-jqnnt",
									"href": "http://steelwagstaff.com/favorite-artists-series-3-george-oppen/"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-26-f5hy6",
									"href": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drug_Abuse_Resistance_Education#/media/File:Drug_Abuse_Resistance_Education_DARE_Logo.png"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-44-zxse9",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-30-awxhh",
									"text": "Aub:\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-31-cw1aq",
									"text": "Mary says you phoned -- in evangelical mood [Apparently she was inviting them to come visit her and, among other things, try marijuana]. I answer by letter not for formality nor even for emphasis, but only because I spend so much time at a desk, and do have to change the subject occasionally, so that it is easier to write than to phone. And here are the things I would say, duly numbered:\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-32-zg9y5",
									"text": "1. One gets rather well occupied by the time one is 56, and there is simply not time for major excursions.   I mean – I really don’t have time.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-33-bwoo0",
									"text": "2. I fight automatically and fiercely against derangement of the senses, and have been consciously doing so since I was nineteen. [This is a key age, and a bit heartbreaking, when you know Oppen's biography and background. As a teenager, a few weeks before he was due to graduate from the military academy he had attended for high school, Oppen was the driver in a car accident in which one of his passengers was killed. He was driving drunk. After the accident he was expelled from school, and his family sent him to travel in Europe briefly before coming back to the US and finishing high school.] As witnessed by the first poem in "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-34-hwg4d",
									"text": "Discrete Series",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-35-yczvi",
									"text": ", by the fly leaf of "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-36-bcc28",
									"text": "The Materials",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-37-a1cqz",
									"text": ", and will be again on the fly leaf of This in Which: ‘ . . the third path, the arduous path of appearance’\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-38-0oer3",
									"text": "3. That covers some forty years; a considerable momentum. We’re committed, Mary and I, as artists, and therefore very seriously, to the common, the un-doped, the un-staged, the plain and ordinary daylight. Whatever we see now, we’ll see that way – or fight to do so.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-39-t91md",
									"text": "4. I believe we can’t be astonished by any hallucination whatever. Whereas we are totally astonished by daylight, by any brick in a brick wall we focus on.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-40-zax7d",
									"text": "5. And astonishment – which is a form of stubbornness – is the core of our lives.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-41-3fdze",
									"text": "I speak only for us.   It’s O K. Not for us. Eventually not for you either. Bon Voyage, and keep us in sight, waving avuncular and auntly handkerchiefs on the pier and talking to each other about old times.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-42-p8y8i",
									"text": "And really, really do not get hooked; i.e., don’t try narcotics at all.  But I’m sure you know that.   And don’t escalate marijuana.   It’s serious;  we can give you horrendous reports from the Mexican hospitals, if you need them.   We saw.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-43-8qpkq",
									"text": "George"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-49-psn7v",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-45-v0sg2",
									"text": "Is that not the best "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-47-qphkt",
									"text": "DARE",
									"marks": [
										"key-46-qlajm"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-48-90j1f",
									"text": " newsletter you could ever imagine? When my kids turn 12 [or whatever age kids start doing drugs 15-20 years from now], I've putting a poster of this up in their rooms. Oppen apparently also wrote a letter to his daughter Linda with a one paragraph \"report on the commerce between me and marijuana\" in which he tells her"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-46-qlajm",
									"href": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drug_Abuse_Resistance_Education"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-51-eju54",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-50-rnrn6",
									"text": "I do not in the least like it; I continue to believe that I know my actual size, and my actual size seems to me to be an essential part of the matter, as it seems to me that the whole point of anything is that it is as it is. We fall again and again into the idea of higher realms, other spheres, higher and dimmer heavens in which wonderful things will happen and all doubts be answered. But I think in this way we answer the doubt before it is felt, and solve the mystery before we have encountered it. The mystery is that there is something for us to stand on"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-55-3sf4x",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-52-rt951",
									"text": "This closing phrase echoes closely the concluding passage from Oppen's tremendous poem \"World, World--\" the last poem in his collection "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-53-u896t",
									"text": "This in Which",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-54-ev5vy",
									"text": ", which ends:"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-65-bo0dt",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-56-46auz",
									"text": "'Thought leaps on us' because we are here. That is the fact of the matter.\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-57-3xlcl",
									"text": "Soul-searchings, these prescriptions,\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-58-ann1u",
									"text": "Are a medical faddism, an attempt to escape,\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-59-ezyoi",
									"text": "To lose oneself in the self.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-60-n9ki7",
									"text": "The self is no mystery, the mystery is\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-61-akqg8",
									"text": "That there is something for us to stand on.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-62-bvq7y",
									"text": "We want to be here.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-63-pwvec",
									"text": "The act of being, the act of being\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-64-pconr",
									"text": "More than oneself."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-69-bcfmj",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-66-jwfcw",
									"text": "The next book would be "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-67-hy3oy",
									"text": "Of Being Numerous",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-68-pwmhw",
									"text": "."
								}
							]
						}
					]
				}
			},
