						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-103-uh8gk",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-101-slwu3",
									"text": "So, reading this years later, I'm embarrassed at times (especially by the needless profanity), but still a little impressed at how perceptive I was at 15 or 16. There are moments in this piece that I'm kind of proud of, and insights that surprise me--I'm glad that I had the attitude that I did about Gay Pride despite being a young Mormon teen heavily involved in very masculine, gender normative, and largely homophobic sports, and I'm impressed with the attention I give to sensory details and perceptions--I can sense an early desire to show instead of tell. There's probably more to be embarrassed of than proud of, but it's what I wrote, and it was my truth at a certain point in my life.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-102-kh3rt",
									"text": "Now here's the saddest part for me: I don't know what happened to any of the children I mention in the story, my childhood friends and acquaintances. I lived in the same dorm with Jared Crandall during my freshman year at BYU, and when I moved to Oklahoma a few years later, I ran into Trevor Miller and we played baseball together for a few years, but since that time, all of these boyhood friends have vanished from my life. I miss them--Trevor especially--and would love to know where they are and how any of them are doing. And so, dear readers, I turn to you. If you've got any leads, please pass them on. Readers, what are your most vivid memories of childhood? What pieces of writing from your teen years can you dig up, and what feelings do they stir up in you?"
								}
							]
						}
					]
				}
			},
			{
				"id": "posts:distressing-changes-to-wisconsins-mining-laws-proposed-2",
				"slug": "distressing-changes-to-wisconsins-mining-laws-proposed-2",
				"status": "published",
				"data": {
					"title": "Distressing Changes to Wisconsin's Mining Laws Proposed",
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-29-ke173",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-wh0a0",
									"text": "From Monday through Thursday of this week, I toured the state as part of a \""
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-3-xvhp6",
									"text": "Place-Based Workshop",
									"marks": [
										"key-2-1qkxw"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-4-fm3zk",
									"text": "\" put on annually by "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-6-smjrv",
									"text": "The Center for Culture, History, and Environment",
									"marks": [
										"key-5-4j97z"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-7-iygw2",
									"text": " (CHE) at the University of Wisconsin-Madison. I've been one of CHE's "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-9-t8ga9",
									"text": "Graduate Student Affiliates",
									"marks": [
										"key-8-31pbf"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-10-f91z4",
									"text": " for a few years now, but this was the first CHE Place-Based Workshop that I've attended. The theme of this year's workshop was \"Landscapes of Health,\" and I felt really fortunate to be a part of a group of 30+ graduate students, faculty, and friends who traveled all over the state exploring issues of health and wellness. We met all kinds of really interesting people, saw a number of fascinating sites of historical interest, ate some marvelous food, and learned so many things.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-11-7zy3m",
									"text": "On the second day of the trip we traveled to "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-13-75uyx",
									"text": "Crandon, Wisconsin",
									"marks": [
										"key-12-3j0rx"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-14-ibltw",
									"text": ", where a group of local Native Americans (led by Tina Van Zile, a member of the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-16-5x0du",
									"text": "Sakaogan Chippewa",
									"marks": [
										"key-15-ypq6m"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-17-5fsie",
									"text": " community near Mole Lake and Wolf River--watch a brief walking tour of the location "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-19-kl19e",
									"text": "here",
									"marks": [
										"key-18-q68bf"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-20-teys4",
									"text": ") and environmental activists successfully defeated the proposed construction of the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-22-ykule",
									"text": "Crandon Mine",
									"marks": [
										"key-21-xlwpw"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-23-nnvq5",
									"text": " (see the link for a collection of resources hosted by the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources). After several years of legal wrangling with Exxon, the Sakoagan Chippewa and the Forest County Potawatami eventually "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-25-4zqaj",
									"text": "purchased the mining site",
									"marks": [
										"key-24-n4shw"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-26-stt9g",
									"text": " for $16.5 million from Nicolet Minerals in October of 2003.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-27-bxmkc",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_292\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"500\" caption=\"Tina Van Zile, Environmental Director for the Sakaogan Mole Lake Chippewa Band. Glenn Reynolds is partially visible over her left sholder.\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
