						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-7-m54ng",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-wx0ls",
									"text": "When I was 19 years old, just after completing my first year at "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-3-eynep",
									"text": "a large university",
									"marks": [
										"key-2-9ic37"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-4-8jlu9",
									"text": " in the American West, I left school to spend two years as a Mormon missionary in the Northeast of England. When I arrived in Britain, I knew little to nothing about the present social or economic conditions of the cities that I would be living and working in. For the next two years I lived and worked in a string of devastated colliery and fishing towns whose economic centers had been ravaged by Thatcher-era political decisions, particularly the contentious privatization of Britain’s coal industry in the mid 1980s. My last assignment before returning home was in Barnsley, in South Yorkshire.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-5-czl8w",
									"text": "[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"800\"]"
								}
							],
