								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-14-p9qvz",
									"text": " National Union of Mineworkers (Great Britain) (Photo credit: Wikipedia)[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-15-5evla",
									"text": "Barnsley is most famous as the setting for Ken Loach’s iconic film "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-17-uzcb4",
									"text": "Kes",
									"marks": [
										"key-16-1gze6",
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-18-r5cl1",
									"text": " and as the hometown of "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-20-km8yd",
									"text": "Arthur Scargill",
									"marks": [
										"key-19-bi2fb"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-21-jwj57",
									"text": ", the fiery Marxist leader of the National Union of Mineworkers (the principal union of coal miners in the UK) during the ill-fated "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-23-82ah3",
									"text": "1984-5 strike",
									"marks": [
										"key-22-bxfj3"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-24-5vgrk",
									"text": "that culminated in the closure of a substantial percentage of Britain’s coal mines and the layoffs of thousands of workers in Britain’s coal mining communities.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-25-nu5xq",
									"text": "One day we received a media referral from a woman who had seen an advertisement on the television and called to get a free copy of a film made by the Church about Jesus’ life, death, and resurrection called the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-27-cwp95",
									"text": "Lamb of God",
									"marks": [
										"key-26-k7usq"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-28-5zgk5",
									"text": ". Her name was Anne Tyson, and the referral indicated that she lived at 34 Carlton St. in Grimethorpe, a nearby village. Neither of us had been to Grimethorpe, so we took the bus out late on a Thursday morning (it was August 14, 2003, just 3 days after my 21st birthday, actually) to see if we could find her in. When we arrived the city looked decimated. There were kids playing in what looked like a slag heap just across from the bus stop, throwing fragments of brick, glass bottles, and other rubbish at what remained of the streetlights. I’d seen some sad things on my mission, but this looked otherworldly. I felt as if I had entered into a forsaken place.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-29-3ek08",
									"text": "[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"432\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-16-1gze6",
									"href": "http://www.criterion.com/films/27560-kes"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-19-bi2fb",
									"href": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5FPBMjFiPKc"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-22-bxfj3",
									"href": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UK_miners'_strike_(1984%E2%80%931985)"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
