							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-29-rna5d",
									"text": " Back side of our Save the Date postcards.[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-30-yhe9u",
									"text": "On the back, I set the text in "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-32-ffnkn",
									"text": "Franklin Demi Gothic",
									"marks": [
										"key-31-qf4jz"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-33-e1i1n",
									"text": ", a blocky sans-serif font that I liked the look of, especially when it came to numerals. I made the periods separating date/month/year and the url for "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-35-uzrj8",
									"text": "our wedding website",
									"marks": [
										"key-34-v4yxi"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-36-qoik5",
									"text": " look like paint splotches for a bit of excitement, and we also featured a goofy picture of us making bear poses in front of a real bear at the Madison Zoo. I also made sure to leaving enough white space at the bottom of the back for postal barcodes, and the appropriate white space on the right for addresses and postage.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-37-p1jvl",
									"text": "Once the design was finished, I called various printing shops around Madison before settling on "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-39-cpzkc",
									"text": "SprintPrint",
									"marks": [
										"key-38-m3wmp"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-40-zqstz",
									"text": ", who printed 100+ black and white postcards for something like $20. Black and white printing is far less expensive than color printing, so our greatest expense for these cards was postage, which we were able to keep down by mailing postcards instead of envelopes.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-41-aqxar",
									"text": "Invitations:\n",
									"marks": [
										"strong"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-42-xfpgd",
									"text": "Once the Save the Dates were all mailed and we had a date and location confirmed, we started to plan the design for the invitations and RSVPs. I have some experience with InDesign and other tools in the Adobe Creative Suite, and I spent a couple of weeks working on a two-color design for wedding invitations and RSVP cards. We knew going in that we would be inviting roughly 100 guests to the reception and substantially fewer (between 30 and 40) people to the wedding ceremony itself, so I planned to design an invitation that could be printed two-sided for those few invitations that would feature both a reception and ceremony invitation. I went through dozens of drafts and spent way too long tweaking small elements of design (typeface, font size, kerning, spacing, etc.) and finally settled on the designs you see below.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-43-s0rq1",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_962\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"500\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-31-qf4jz",
									"href": "http://www.azfonts.net/load_font/fradm.html"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-34-v4yxi",
									"href": "http://www.laurelandsteel.info"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
