						"provider": "external",
						"id": "",
						"src": "https://steelwagstaff.info/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/img_1970-e1431529356879.jpg"
					},
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-6-uhver",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-tx5su",
									"text": "I have an approved dissertation proposal! What's its title, you ask? Get ready, because it's really sexy. "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-2-0kbxy",
									"text": "\"Thinking with the things as they exist”: Ecocriticism and Objectivist Poetics.",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-3-piyaq",
									"text": " Yeah. A thrilling tour through what I'm calling an \"Objectivist\" poetics (the writing of George Oppen, Lorine Niedecker, Louis Zukofsky, Charles Reznikoff, Basil Bunting, William Carlos Williams, and maybe, just maybe, a little Carl Rakosi!!!), ecocriticism, phenomenology, with a dash of animal-human relations and a pinch or two of what the kids are calling speculative materialism or OOO (Object-Oriented Ontology--not that so elegant intelligent Shakespehearean rag T.S. Eliot was on about in \"The Wasteland\"--that was O O O O, of course.) Hopefully you'll be able to read it within the next couple of years.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-4-500df",
									"text": "[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"487\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-5-2g0lk",
									"href": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/img_1970.jpg"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-7-pszft",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/img_1970.jpg?w=487",
								"url": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/img_1970.jpg?w=487"
							},
							"alt": "Photograph of Pearl Bailey"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-9-th9b0",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-8-tydaf",
									"text": " Sadly, this title was already taken. It's a wonder my committee still approved the proposal.[/caption]"
								}
							]
						}
					]
				}
			},
			{
				"id": "posts:lorine-matchmaker-love-story",
				"slug": "lorine-matchmaker-love-story",
				"status": "published",
				"data": {
					"title": "Lorine Was Our Matchmaker: A Love Story",
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-6-sll4k",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-iui58",
									"text": "It's been a long while since I've posted anything here. I'm getting married next month, and much of the past several months has been filled with my preparations for the wedding--with doing things that will make the event more meaningful, memorable, and consistent with our values and ideals. As part of this process, we've made wedding rings for each other under the incredible tutelage of the wonderful Hiroko Yamada, master metalsmith and co-owner of the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-3-urjhy",
									"text": "HYART gallery",
									"marks": [
										"key-2-a3syq"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-4-g9h87",
									"text": " in Madison, and recently designed and printed our wedding announcements a Vandercook letterpress (super interesting! but more on this in a future post). Both experiences were fantastic, and we've learned a lot and grown in love and respect for each other and for the process of careful attention and craftsman(and -woman)-ship required to make beautiful things.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-5-q9jxy",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_764\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"640\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-2-a3syq",
									"href": "http://hyartgallery.com/about-us/"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-7-jng9h",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2012/03/img_0303.jpg",
								"url": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2012/03/img_0303.jpg"
							},
							"alt": "Our finished rings"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-21-ht3dr",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-8-l78i0",
									"text": "A picture of the finished rings. The ring Laurel made for me is on the left, the rings I made for her are on the right.[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-9-gcxuc",
									"text": "I'm also posting because I recently wrote part of our love story for "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-10-lc7e7",
									"text": "Solitary Plover",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-11-ykdr5",
									"text": ", the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-13-nuly7",
									"text": "Friends of Lorine Niedecker",
									"marks": [
										"key-12-l8y6t"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-14-347i9",
									"text": "'s biannual newsletter. Ann Engelman, the president of the Friends and a really wonderful woman to boot, requested that Laurel and I write our story for their publication, since attending the Lorine Niedecker festival was an important event in our having grown to love one another. I wrote a brief account of the role that Lorine's poetry played in our current happiness called \"Lorine Was Our Matchmaker\", which you can read in the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-16-yff48",
									"text": "Winter 2012 issue",
									"marks": [
										"key-15-bywkn"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-17-dk2rz",
									"text": " of the newsletter. In case you can't get the PDF to open correctly, "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-19-p4nqy",
									"text": "here's a locally hosted version",
									"marks": [
										"key-18-6xgts"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-20-lt908",
									"text": "."
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-12-l8y6t",
									"href": "http://lorineniedecker.org/"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-15-bywkn",
									"href": "http://www.lorineniedecker.org/documents/Winter2012.pdf#page=3"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-18-6xgts",
									"href": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2012/03/winter2012.pdf"
								}
							]
						}
					],
					"excerpt": "<img src=\"http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2012/03/img_0303.jpg\" alt=\"Our finished rings\" class=\"size-full wp-image-764\" /><p>A picture of the finished rings. The ring Laurel made for me is on the left, the rings I made for her are on the right.</p>"
				}
			},
			{
				"id": "posts:on-seeing-the-one-thing-clearly",
				"slug": "on-seeing-the-one-thing-clearly",
				"status": "published",
				"data": {
					"title": "On Seeing the One Thing Clearly",
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-2-gjum7",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-cx0ay",
									"text": "I've spent much of the past week trying with increasing desperation to write a dissertation proposal. It's been the academic task that I've been ostensibly working on for nearly 18 months now, since I passed my prelims in early fall 2010. I don't know what it has been so difficult for me to do, or to focus on, or to think about, but at times I've felt almost paralyzed by doubt and indecision. Sometimes thinking carefully and grandly about a subject that you expect to devote considerable time and energy about and a position that you hope to advance over the course of thousands of words opens you up to all kinds of fear--fear of not knowing enough, fear of failing to achieve originality, fear of being profoundly and deeply mistaken, fear of misreading, dishonesty, error. I sent off a rough draft of the proposal today, and as I've reflected on the struggles I've had with dissertation proposal writing, a few lines from George Oppen have persisted in my memory. They come from section 27 of his tremendous long poem \"Of Being Numerous\":"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-8-yspx1",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-3-an217",
									"text": "One must not come to feel that he has a thousand threads in his hands,\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-4-awyui",
									"text": "He must somehow see the one thing;\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-5-efxl9",
									"text": "This is the level of art\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-6-9xda9",
									"text": "There are other levels\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-7-7xzs2",
									"text": "But there is no other level of art"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-10-8lcwc",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-9-hmltk",
									"text": "I confess to something akin to bewilderment mingled with admiration for such an idea--such an ambition. I very much feel as though I have a thousand threads in my hands and am struggling to see the one thing. And so there is for me, in this task, as in so many others a felt necessity to arrive at some greater precision, some usefulness, some method of seeing and saying that offers something to someone else, even if as is the case with this dissertation, I'm not entirely sure who that someone else might be. Still, I'm glad to have chosen to write about poets who I admire so fiercely, women like Lorine Niedecker and men like George Oppen, who not only has given me the challenge of seeing the one thing but who wrote in the concluding lines of the first section of the poem \"Route\":"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-15-x17vp",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-11-kka7n",
									"text": "Clarity, clarity, sure clarity is the most beautiful thing in the world,\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-12-gkqku",
									"text": "A limited, limiting clarity\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-13-qe96h",
									"text": "I have not and never did have any motive of poetry\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-14-mwhqo",
									"text": "But to achieve clarity."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-18-peslf",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-16-4tjgc",
									"text": "I find a statement of this kind daunting, but there's something about it that I also find beautiful. I want to make this my ambition: to write my dissertation carefully, honestly, clearly, without the desperate feeling of having a thousand threads in my hands, but still capable of acknowledging the ways that I am limited and limiting. If anyone reading this has any insight or advice into seeing the one thing when it comes to a large academic writing project or into achieving clarity, please share your thoughts with me. I could use them.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-17-olkfx",
									"text": "[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"650\"]"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-19-fex4f",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://www.sjphoto.com/geo_mary.jpeg",
								"url": "http://www.sjphoto.com/geo_mary.jpeg"
							},
							"alt": "photograph of George and Mary Oppen"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-21-gkuf3",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-20-9305w",
									"text": "George and Mary Oppen, photograph by Stephen Johnson[/caption]"
								}
							]
						}
					]
				}
			},
			{
				"id": "posts:lorine-niedecker-and-the-99",
				"slug": "lorine-niedecker-and-the-99",
				"status": "published",
				"data": {
					"title": "Lorine Niedecker and the 99%",
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-29-5vhbl",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-f2pzj",
									"text": "One my favorite poets ever was "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-3-0v1rs",
									"text": "Lorine Niedecker",
									"marks": [
										"key-2-yvzhf"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-4-23q3v",
									"text": ", a remarkable woman who spent most of her life living and writing on Blackhawk Island on the Rock River, just outside of "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-6-yn12s",
									"text": "Fort Atkinson",
									"marks": [
										"key-5-7s3zw"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-7-te4np",
									"text": ", Wisconsin. At her death, she left behind "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-9-yelv8",
									"text": "a little library",
									"marks": [
										"key-8-qnoep"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-10-a9ol6",
									"text": " (including her now infamous '"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-12-e9yc3",
									"text": "Immortal Cupboard",
									"marks": [
										"key-11-0so5u"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-13-o2ztv",
									"text": "', which consisted of, among other things, her treasured copies of \"Marcus Aurelius [his "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-15-yjks3",
									"text": "Meditations",
									"marks": [
										"em",
										"key-14-r3j5r"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-16-ne9o2",
									"text": "], Thoreau’s Walden and "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-18-pyr5v",
									"text": "Japanese Haiku",
									"marks": [
										"key-17-lwod6"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-19-9ivy3",
									"text": " and standing beside that is [Louis Zukofsky’s] Test of Poetry\" (letter to Zukofsky, June 1, 1958)). Her books were donated to the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-21-pcig5",
									"text": "Dwight Foster Public Library",
									"marks": [
										"key-20-k7vu9"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-22-jzz1j",
									"text": " by her widower Al Millen where they were permitted to circulate with the rest of the library's collection for some time, before librarians recognized the unique historical treasure they had been given, and built a small little historical exhibit that you can still visit and peruse. The first time I went to see Niedecker's library, I went first to her 1927 "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-23-grcak",
									"text": "Everyman's Library ",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-24-9re7z",
									"text": "copy of Thoreau's "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-25-ic2zs",
									"text": "Walden ",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-26-8vucx",
									"text": "(which also has a special place in my own immortal cupboard) and found between the cover and title page a small yellowing slip of paper on which Lorine had written in her gentle cursive script: “Of Thoreau - He chose to be rich by making his wants few. – Emerson”. I was enormously touched.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-27-kapuj",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_751\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"494\" caption=\"Lorine Niedecker, reading (Walden, I hope)\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-2-yvzhf",
									"href": "http://uwpress.wisc.edu/books/4779.htm"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-5-7s3zw",
									"href": "http://uwdc.library.wisc.edu/collections/WI/FortAtkinsonLocHist"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-8-qnoep",
									"href": "http://www.lorineniedecker.org/lndb.html"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-11-0so5u",
									"href": "http://cccook.wordpress.com/2009/03/13/43/"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-14-r3j5r",
									"href": "http://lorineniedecker.org/resources_display.cfm?rid=148"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-17-lwod6",
									"href": "http://lorineniedecker.org/resources_display.cfm?rid=47"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-20-k7vu9",
									"href": "http://lorineniedecker.org/archive.cfm"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-28-v8sl1",
									"href": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/12/lorine-reading1.jpg"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-30-71aez",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/12/lorine-reading1.jpg",
								"url": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/12/lorine-reading1.jpg"
							},
							"alt": "Lorine Niedecker, reading a book"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-57-hbpfs",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-31-s21cr",
									"text": "[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-32-evtex",
									"text": "I spent most of that day looking for Niedecker marginalia. It was one of the best days I've ever spent researching anything. A few months later I was stunned and overjoyed to learn that "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-34-dx77v",
									"text": "Tom Montag",
									"marks": [
										"key-33-cvjly"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-35-ity0p",
									"text": " had spent more than 120 hours carefully going through all of Lorine's surviving books and recording her marginal annotations. You can see "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-37-v10uz",
									"text": "them all",
									"marks": [
										"key-36-oc9o4"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-38-e4jd5",
									"text": " on the Friends of Lorine Niedecker website.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-39-kuml1",
									"text": "I'm posting this because of a chance discovery I made in that marginalia earlier this week while I was looking for something else. I saw with interest that Lorine owned a copy of legendary Wisconsin Senator and "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-41-4ak88",
									"text": "Progressive Party",
									"marks": [
										"key-40-1jmop"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-42-9hpyk",
									"text": " leader "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-44-vcmtx",
									"text": "Robert La Follette",
									"marks": [
										"key-43-g7ua1"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-45-9boig",
									"text": "'s "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-47-qqy3r",
									"text": "Political Philosophy",
									"marks": [
										"key-46-2rgpi"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-48-i4otw",
									"text": " (published in 1920), the inside cover of which says simply, \"Lorine Niedecker - Junior Year\" (she graduated from high school in 1922). The annotation that caught my eye wasn't particularly expressive, in fact, all Niedecker had done was to mark the passage with brackets. It was the contents of the passage itself that interested me, particularly in light of the recent political protests here in Madison (and the ongoing '"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-50-x8gel",
									"text": "Recall Walker",
									"marks": [
										"key-49-wua8j"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-51-mrlx6",
									"text": "' [and Kleefisch] movements) and the burgeoning Occupy [ ] and We Are the 99% movements. In a speech given on the Senate Floor in September 1917 (a time of war) responding to objections made by Senator "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-53-wyg4g",
									"text": "Porter McCumber",
									"marks": [
										"key-52-p5a42"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-54-bkpmb",
									"text": " (North Dakota) regarding a 'War Profits Tax', La Follette asks: \"Who does the senator think are the people of this country? Is it the 2 per cent, owners of two-thirds of the wealth, or is it the 98 per cent of the population who have to divide among themselves the meager balance of this country's wealth, which, apportioned among them per capita, is a little over $800 apiece?\" La Follette's math needs only slight updating, and the current mood is even slightly more inclusive (\"We\"--\"We the People\"--\"The people of this country\" are now the \"99%\" rather than La Follette's \"98 per cent\"), but the sentiment seems remarkable relevant, and I'm pleased to see traces of the deep roots of Wisconsin Progressivism made visible in the material history of Lorine Niedecker's reading practices.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-55-g6l0j",
									"text": "[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"600\" caption=\"La Follette with his family in 1917, the year he delivered the speech cited above.\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-33-cvjly",
									"href": "http://middlewesterner.typepad.com/about.html"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-36-oc9o4",
									"href": "http://www.lorineniedecker.org/notes.htm"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-40-1jmop",
									"href": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Progressive_Party_(United_States,_1924)"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-43-g7ua1",
									"href": "http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/whi/results.asp?keyword1=Robert+M%2E+La+Follette%2C+Sr%2E&search_field1=description&search_type=advanced&sort_by=date&boolean_type=and"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-46-2rgpi",
									"href": "http://www.archive.org/details/politicalphilos00follgoog"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-49-wua8j",
									"href": "http://www.unitedwisconsin.com/"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-52-p5a42",
									"href": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Porter_J._McCumber"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-56-jz46w",
									"href": "http://images.wisconsinhistory.org/700099990184/9999003632-l.jpg"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-58-yhp5f",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://images.wisconsinhistory.org/700099990184/9999003632-l.jpg",
								"url": "http://images.wisconsinhistory.org/700099990184/9999003632-l.jpg"
							},
							"alt": "photograph of Robert M. La Follette with his Family"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-83-3vzjb",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-59-pbeiv",
									"text": "[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-60-g0oms",
									"text": "It seems also to me that there is an interesting connection between the two chance passages I've noted in this blog post--Emerson's idea of Thoreau's richness consisting in a voluntary austerity and La Follette's excoriation of the 2 per cent who own a full two-thirds of the nation's wealth. While there is a certain stoical wisdom in pursing that kind of '"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-62-ms3zb",
									"text": "poverty that enjoys true wealth",
									"marks": [
										"key-61-gt85e"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-63-76ifn",
									"text": "', there is also a very real danger in following too ardently the Thoreauvian path of contentment with few wants (or the Christian version of 'noble poverty' expressed memorably in 1 Timothy 6:6: \"godliness with contentment is great gain\"), inasmuch as such a choice might resign us seeing the sometimes crushing meagerness of others' material conditions as a basic, inalterable social fact--something along the lines of the shoulder-shrugging, responsibility-shirking way some Christians seem to interpret Jesus' remark that \"The poor ye have with you always\" (Mark 14:7). It seems to me that Niedecker chose quite clearly to both see herself as one of the 98 per cent--I do wonder what her \"I am the 99%\" missive might have looked like, though I doubt she would have written something so confessional, much less photographed herself holding it--as well as one who, like Thoreau, strove to be rich by keeping her wants few. I do think, though, that however much we consciously limit the proliferation of our own consumptive desires, we should not extend a similar restraint forcibly upon others, but allow for the flowering of a vast diffusion of desires and wants in our fellow beings, a flowering which requires some basic conditions of comfort, peace, and fertility. I suppose that what I am really trying to say is that no matter how few we make our wants, it seems imperative to me that among them we must retain the desire that forms the heart of George Oppen's remarkable poem "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-65-ykm0i",
									"text": "\"Street\"",
									"marks": [
										"key-64-x21nm"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-66-se821",
									"text": ", namely an \"end of poverty\" and the \"real pain\" that so often accompanies it:\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-67-nfez4",
									"text": "STREET\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-68-rkjrr",
									"text": "Ah these are the poor,\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-69-xgzno",
									"text": "These are the poor-Bergen street.\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-70-4r7ho",
									"text": "Humiliation,\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-71-gdx0g",
									"text": "Hardship...\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-72-w53ub",
									"text": "Nor are they very good to each other;\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-73-od67u",
									"text": "It is not that. I want\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-74-bbf0y",
									"text": "An end of poverty\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-75-xtges",
									"text": "As much as anyone\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-76-xjb2m",
									"text": "For the sake of intelligence,\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-77-1zcah",
									"text": "'The conquest of existence'-\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-78-eta70",
									"text": "It has been said, and is true\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-79-3rpsv",
									"text": "And this is real pain,\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-80-hxk11",
									"text": "Moreover. It is terrible to see the children,\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-81-qyp3g",
									"text": "The righteous little girls;\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-82-ummgr",
									"text": "So good, they expect to be so good....\n\n"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-61-gt85e",
									"href": "http://books.google.com/books?id=YXJbAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA164#v=onepage&q&f=false"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-64-x21nm",
									"href": "http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/21479"
								}
							]
						}
					]
				}
			},
			{
				"id": "posts:lorine-niedecker-99",
				"slug": "lorine-niedecker-99",
				"status": "draft",
				"data": {
					"title": "Lorine Niedecker and the 99%",
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-48-ycmzr",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-g44d3",
									"text": "One my favorite poets ever was "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-3-qiqbs",
									"text": "Lorine Niedecker",
									"marks": [
										"key-2-woxn5"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-4-arud5",
									"text": ", a remarkable woman who spent most of her life living and writing on Blackhawk Island on the Rock River, just outside of "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-6-b7roh",
									"text": "Fort Atkinson",
									"marks": [
										"key-5-cyeca"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-7-2avac",
									"text": ", Wisconsin. At her death, she left behind "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-9-p982c",
									"text": "a little library",
									"marks": [
										"key-8-62v2l"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-10-rncot",
									"text": " (including her now infamous '"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-12-j6l10",
									"text": "Immortal Cupboard",
									"marks": [
										"key-11-ogj79"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-13-eo7o5",
									"text": "', which consisted of, among other things, her treasured copies of \"Marcus Aurelius [his "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-15-fvkoa",
									"text": "Meditations",
									"marks": [
										"em",
										"key-14-w4wga"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-16-14ban",
									"text": "], Thoreau’s Walden and "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-18-04z4l",
									"text": "Japanese Haiku",
									"marks": [
										"key-17-nj6hi"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-19-fw6xy",
									"text": " and standing beside that is [Louis Zukofsky’s] Test of Poetry\" (letter to Zukofsky, June 1, 1958)). Her books were donated to the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-21-ty635",
									"text": "Dwight Foster Public Library",
									"marks": [
										"key-20-h1b1h"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-22-l4h9v",
									"text": " by her widower Al Millen where they were permitted to circulate with the rest of the library's collection for some time, before librarians recognized the unique historical treasure they had been given, and built a small little historical exhibit that you can still visit and peruse. The first time I went to see Niedecker's library, I went first to her 1927 "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-23-xc4gz",
									"text": "Everyman's Library ",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-24-iceuq",
									"text": "copy of Thoreau's "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-25-1gmcs",
									"text": "Walden ",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-26-jedjm",
									"text": "(which also has a special place in my own immortal cupboard) and found between the cover and title page a small yellowing slip of paper on which Lorine had written in her gentle cursive script: “Of Thoreau - He chose to be rich by making his wants few. – Emerson”. I was enormously touched.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-27-qaibs",
									"text": "I spent most of that day looking for Niedecker marginalia. It was one of the best days I've ever spent researching anything. A few months later I was stunned and overjoyed to learn that "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-29-f3jkr",
									"text": "Tom Montag",
									"marks": [
										"key-28-w6sw0"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-30-cl5qr",
									"text": " had spent more than 120 hours carefully going through all of Lorine's surviving books and recording her marginal annotations. You can see "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-32-tiybo",
									"text": "them all",
									"marks": [
										"key-31-8dym6"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-33-bmelj",
									"text": " on the Friends of Lorine Niedecker website.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-34-hivpr",
									"text": "I'm posting this because of a chance discovery I made in that marginalia earlier this week while I was looking for something else. I saw with interest that Lorine owned a copy of legendary Wisconsin Senator and Progressive Party leader Robert La Follette's "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-36-8qkx5",
									"text": "Political Philosophy",
									"marks": [
										"key-35-vo6ge"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-37-n1jxv",
									"text": " (published in 1920), the inside cover of which says simply, \"Lorine Niedecker - Junior Year\" (she graduated from high school in 1922). The annotation that caught my eye wasn't particularly expressive, in fact, all Niedecker had done was to mark the passage with brackets. It was the contents of the passage itself that interested me, particularly in light of the recent political protests here in Madison (and the ongoing '"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-39-n02fz",
									"text": "Recall Walker",
									"marks": [
										"key-38-x7srf"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-40-nvfku",
									"text": "' [and Kleefisch] movements) and the burgeoning Occupy [ ] and We Are the 99% movements. In a speech responding to Senator "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-42-u0wac",
									"text": "Porter McCumber",
									"marks": [
										"key-41-piut9"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-43-dg0wk",
									"text": " (North Dakota), La Follette asks: \"Who does the senator think are the people of this country? Is it the 2 per cent, owners of two-thirds of the wealth, or is it the 98 per cent of the population who have to divide among themselves the meager balance of this country's wealth, which, apportioned among them per capita, is a little over $800 apiece?\" La Follette's math needs only slight updating, and the current mood is even slightly more inclusive (\"We\"--\"We the People\"--\"The people of this country\" are now the \"99%\" rather than La Follette's \"98 per cent\"), but the sentiment seems remarkable relevant, and I'm pleased to see visible traces of the deep roots of Progressivism growing out Wisconsin's past in the material history of Lorine Niedecker's reading practices. \n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-44-l295z",
									"text": "It seems also to me that there is an interesting connection between the two chance passages I've noted in this blog post--Emerson's idea of Thoreau's richness consisting in a voluntary austerity and La Follette's excoriation of the 2 per cent who own a full two-thirds of the nation's wealth. While there is a certain stoical wisdom in pursing that kind of '"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-46-5h4h0",
									"text": "poverty that enjoys true wealth",
									"marks": [
										"key-45-u24cs"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-47-equuw",
									"text": "', there is also a very real danger in following too ardently the Thoreauvian path of contentment with few wants (or the Christian version of 'noble poverty' expressed memorably in 1 Timothy 6:6: \"godliness with contentment is great gain\"), inasmuch as such a choice might resign us seeing the sometimes crushing meagerness of others' material conditions as a basic, inalterable social fact--something along the lines of the shoulder-shrugging, responsibility-shirking way some Christians seem to interpret Jesus' remark that \"The poor ye have with you always\" (Mark 14:7). It seems to me that Niedecker chose quite clearly to both see herself as one of the 98 per cent--I do wonder what her \"I am the 99%\" missive might have looked like, though I doubt she would have written something so confessional, much less photographed herself holding it--as well as one who, like Thoreau, strove to be rich by keeping her wants few. I do think, though, that however much we consciously limit the proliferation of our own consumptive desires, we should not extend a similar restraint forcibly upon others, but allow for the flowering of a vast diffusion of desires and wants in our fellow beings, a flowering which requires some basic conditions of comfort, peace, and fertility. I suppose that what I am really trying to say is that no matter how few we make our wants, it seems imperative to me that among them we must retain the desire that forms the heart of George Oppen's remarkable poem \"Street\", namely an \"end of poverty\" and the \"real pain\" that so often accompanies it:"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
