				}
			},
			{
				"id": "posts:death-making-memorials",
				"slug": "death-making-memorials",
				"status": "draft",
				"data": {
					"title": "On Death and the Making of Memorials",
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-14-7whh9",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-kopag",
									"text": "It's a huge subject, death. I know this, and yet I still want to write about it today.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-2-arkiy",
									"text": "Two stories from StoryCorps that moved me recently: Brian Korbon: "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-4-qbarp",
									"text": "http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=120580047",
									"marks": [
										"key-3-zohwe"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-5-f7xfr",
									"text": " + "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-7-asgn2",
									"text": "http://storycorps.org/listen/stories/gregg-korbon-and-his-wife-kathryn/\n",
									"marks": [
										"key-6-154iw"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-8-7veqk",
									"text": "David Shea: "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-10-h92wo",
									"text": "http://storycorps.org/listen/stories/david-shea-and-alice-doyle/\n",
									"marks": [
										"key-9-eoij5"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-12-p2dzm",
									"text": "A Poor Wayfaring Man of Grief",
									"marks": [
										"key-11-b2g2w"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-13-j0ztl",
									"text": ":"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-3-zohwe",
									"href": "http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=120580047"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-6-154iw",
									"href": "http://storycorps.org/listen/stories/gregg-korbon-and-his-wife-kathryn/"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-9-eoij5",
									"href": "http://storycorps.org/listen/stories/david-shea-and-alice-doyle/"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-11-b2g2w",
									"href": "http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E4axKHtMNKw"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-17-cqgqe",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-15-2ob6b",
									"text": "\"These deeds shall thy memorial be,\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-16-ggxjs",
									"text": "fear not, thou didst them unto me.\""
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-22-0afyp",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-18-0rizg",
									"text": "Reznikoff:\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-19-4gval",
									"text": "The war may, however, have been the reason why he printed, on the press which he had installed in the basement of his parents’ home in Brooklyn,a small selection of his poems, which he called "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-20-v6day",
									"text": "Rhythms",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-21-waemc",
									"text": ". This little book appeared in 1918, and among the verses was “On One Whom the Germans Shot,” lines inspired by Ezra Pound’s memorial to his gifted friend, the sculptor Henri Gaudier-Brzeska, killed in battle in France in 1915:"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-27-6o1zs",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-23-xxya6",
									"text": "How shall we mourn you who are spilled and wasted,\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-24-he2w2",
									"text": "Gaudier-Brzeska,\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-25-4w1ug",
									"text": "sure that you would not die with your work unended,\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-26-k3fkf",
									"text": "as if the iron scythe in the grass stops for a flower?"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-42-in6i7",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-28-u5g1i",
									"text": "When he reprinted the poem in 1920 he dropped the title, and in 1927 he dropped Gaudier-Brzeska name, but the remaining lines (which Zukofsky praised in the February 1931 “Objectivists’ Issue” of "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-29-3ytdq",
									"text": "Poetry",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-30-udlpk",
									"text": ") are evidence of the thoughts of death which were haunting so many young men like Reznikoff during the war.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-31-1cq8l",
									"text": "--from "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-33-5nhy4",
									"text": "http://www.poetryfoundation.org/bio/charles-reznikoff\n",
									"marks": [
										"key-32-fcuya"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-34-4lurw",
									"text": "J.V. Cunningham\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-35-efa2j",
									"text": "The art of obituaries. Economist book of obituaries and others\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-36-jbmhz",
									"text": "beside the art of elegy--another day.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-37-jmduf",
									"text": "Grace Paley's mother: "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-39-c6qix",
									"text": "http://readashort.blogspot.com/2008/06/mother-by-grace-paley.html\n",
									"marks": [
										"key-38-u7sff"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-40-h57pz",
									"text": "Shakespeare, St. Crispin's day?\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-41-d3wpa",
									"text": "Epitaphs for Niedecker:"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-32-fcuya",
									"href": "http://www.poetryfoundation.org/bio/charles-reznikoff"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-38-u7sff",
									"href": "http://readashort.blogspot.com/2008/06/mother-by-grace-paley.html"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-44-sf6hz",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-43-lce01",
									"text": "For L.N. by Allen Ginsberg"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-47-dyvq5",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-45-xpoit",
									"text": "as her breath was\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-46-u2z8l",
									"text": "now her body,"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-50-nx50y",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-48-0sif0",
									"text": "lonely poet\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-49-nacqz",
									"text": "far from cities"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-52-gfy4i",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-51-lmw7n",
									"text": "one in the world."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-54-zlbgc",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-53-frncv",
									"text": "Bunting for Niedecker: To abate what swells / use ice for scalpel. / It melts in its wound / and no one can tell / what the surgeon used. / Clear lymph, no scar, / no swathe from a cheek’s bloom"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-56-gzjrm",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-55-zvt9r",
									"text": "Niedecker for Bunting: \"The Ballad of Basil\""
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-75-m472y",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-57-mw4s3",
									"text": "They sank the sea\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-58-k4i2w",
									"text": "\tAll land\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-59-i5wdc",
									"text": "\t\tenemy\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-60-n6vsi",
									"text": "He saw his boats stand\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-61-1evhe",
									"text": "\tand he\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-62-jb9hx",
									"text": "\t\toff the floor\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-63-ekzuz",
									"text": "of that cold jail\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-64-5g9un",
									"text": "\t(would not fight\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-65-korbl",
									"text": "\t\ttheir war)\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-66-3t5o0",
									"text": "sailed anyway\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-67-xr6cy",
									"text": "\tVillon went along\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-68-3ec57",
									"text": "\t\tChomei\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-69-t857z",
									"text": "Dante\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-70-ctxrx",
									"text": "\tand the Persian\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-71-ae41t",
									"text": "\t\tFirdusi--\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-72-xrovz",
									"text": "rigging\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-73-sef6l",
									"text": "\tfor his own\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-74-xdk3x",
									"text": "\t\tsinging"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-82-sakhl",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-77-pp7tj",
									"text": "http://media.sas.upenn.edu/pennsound/authors/Niedecker/Niedecker-Lorine_02_The-Ballad-of-Basil_Factory-School-Archive_11-1970.mp3\n",
									"marks": [
										"key-76-keoyj"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-78-1t2zd",
									"text": "Kubler-Ross On death and dying\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-79-ry31p",
									"text": "Vollmann rising up rising down\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-80-mvn30",
									"text": "Becker's "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-81-usbpm",
									"text": "Denial of Death",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-76-keoyj",
									"href": "http://media.sas.upenn.edu/pennsound/authors/Niedecker/Niedecker-Lorine_02_The-Ballad-of-Basil_Factory-School-Archive_11-1970.mp3"
								}
							]
						}
					]
				}
			},
			{
				"id": "posts:the-last-thing-to-go",
				"slug": "the-last-thing-to-go",
				"status": "published",
				"data": {
					"title": "The Last Thing To Go",
					"featured_image": {
						"provider": "external",
						"id": "",
						"src": "https://steelwagstaff.info/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/CHFight.jpg"
					},
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-4-neulk",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-zsfa3",
									"text": "I play basketball on Wednesday nights. Pick-up games, at a church building in Madison, five on five, really nice courts. So it's on my mind today. I've played basketball ever since I was a kid. I've always been into sports, and have always liked playing them more than watching them. Commercials don't help--I abhor them, and televised sporting events are filled with them, with the glorious exception of soccer, which is the sport I watch the most of these days, but I've never been much of a live sports aficionado either. Mostly I think it's because whenever I'm watching other bodies run and move and play, I wish I was doing it myself. I'm not much of a \"true fan\" in the traditional sense, either. I don't understand people who root passionately for the same team ever year. It seems as dumb as nationalism, or brand lust, or any number of other prejudices. I identify 100% with Chuck Klosterman when he "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-3-x55v4",
									"text": "writes ",
									"marks": [
										"key-2-mh3sv"
									]
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-2-mh3sv",
									"href": "http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=simmons/050927&num=0"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-6-hs9gn",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-5-1dwde",
									"text": "I absolutely do not understand why you believe geography should have any significance on which teams you are somehow \"obligated\" to support. That will always strike me as the most irrational reason for liking anything. There is no inherent regional quality to pro sports, beyond the imaginary relationship created by fans. I remember when I lived in Akron, Ohio, during the late 1990s, and it was suddenly announced that the Browns were returning to Cleveland. People in Northeast Ohio immediately began insisting that the Browns were their favorite team; this was before the expansion draft. People were buying Browns' jerseys before they had acquired any players. They didn't even have a coach or a GM. It was a wholly theoretical franchise. So -- essentially -- these people were rooting for (a) an incorporated municipality with a shared tax base, and (b) a color best-described as \"burnt orange.\" These things have nothing to do with football, and you should never like any specific team more than you like the sport itself. ... Basically, I am an intense fan of sports, but I am able to detach from the insane tendency of just rooting for any given team out of habit. And I'll never understand why so many smart people refuse to think critically about sports. ... I don't see why it would be \"honorable\" to support anything unconditionally. That kind of thinking has been the source of almost every significant problem in the entire world, except for maybe the hurricanes."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-10-56h36",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-7-d0vjl",
									"text": "Like Klosterman, I like sports, not teams--though I'll occasionally try to pick a 'favorite' team in whatever sport I'm following and try to track their success, though I can rarely muster any sustained enthusiasm about it, and always feel slightly frightened when I talk to anyone who identifies as a \"true fan\" of whatever team I've chosen. I usually feel like they're crazy, which I guess is kind of the point, but it's really easy to forget that \"fan\" is short for \"fanatic\" when I'm not talking to one. I'm convinced that the reason why I both like sports but not teams and enjoy playing but not watching sports is because my dad was in the Air Force. We moved a lot when I was a child--by the time I graduated from high school, I had attended 13 different public schools, which had two sports related consequences: 1) I never really developed and shared a deep regional attachment to any professional franchise and 2) I gravitated towards sports as a means of adaptation into new social environments. For me, sports were the easiest way to socialize and become accepted by other young boys when I arrived at a new school. So I played them, and my success and skill at them helped to normalize and ingratiate me among my new classmates. It helped that I liked them, mostly.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-8-t08zl",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_85\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"220\" caption=\"Steel Wagstaff, Third Grader\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-9-2joyj",
									"href": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/steel_3rd_grade.jpg"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-11-665aq",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/steel_3rd_grade.jpg?w=220",
								"url": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/steel_3rd_grade.jpg?w=220"
							},
							"alt": "School Photo of Steel Wagstaff in the Third Grade"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-16-wz8e4",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-12-9vebc",
									"text": "[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-13-i9o34",
									"text": "From 2nd until 4th grade, I was the fastest kid in my school, which won me a lot of respect, especially since I was white--what's striking to me in recalling this now is realizing the degree to which most of us children had already absorbed, accepted, and had begun policing and maintaining racially suspect theories of innate athletic ability. Being fast certainly did more for me with my peers than winning the school spelling bee (which I did, but was so nervous at the district spelling bee that I misspelled my first word: \"strength.\" At the time, I actually considered my early exit fortunate because I had peed my pants a little while I was standing at the microphone trying to spell out the word. It wasn't a full-on puddle, and I was fortunate to be wearing black trousers, but it definitely would have been both visible and conspicuous in later rounds. It should be obvious at this point that I was not what you'd generally class as \"cool\".).\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-14-sl3mv",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_86\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"220\" caption=\"Steel Wagstaff, Fourth Grader\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-15-qconw",
									"href": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/steel_4th_grade.jpg"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-17-bvtw6",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/steel_4th_grade.jpg?w=220",
								"url": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/steel_4th_grade.jpg?w=220"
							},
							"alt": "School photo of Steel Wagstaff in 4th grade"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-32-bxn65",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-18-ba5pa",
									"text": "[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-19-vdh5c",
									"text": "In 4th grade, I started at a new school, "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-21-qx02x",
									"text": "Cordova Gardens",
									"marks": [
										"key-20-zoxbp"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-22-v9jar",
									"text": ", which which required my being bused off the Air Force base where we lived and into a rougher part of "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-24-0l8mb",
									"text": "Rancho Cordova",
									"marks": [
										"key-23-k8bg6"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-25-nbo40",
									"text": ". My first day there we had an early morning recess, and I joined a group of boys playing football.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-26-rxw90",
									"text": "The fastest kid there was Willie, and he had moves. I remember two unusual things about him: 1) that he had a jheri curl, and 2) that he played without shoes on--I can still see his long white socks flashing and flailing in the air as he danced and juked, trying to evade would-be tacklers. He was electric--the most athletic 4th grader I had ever seen--not very big, but incredibly quick--like a DeSean Jackson or a Darren Sproles. At some point in the game he broke free, and looked sure to score a long touchdown run. I chased him, caught him, and tagged him down. He kept on running and began celebrating his touchdown, but I shouted \"I tagged you back here, you're down.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-27-tdvmv",
									"text": "He looked shocked that I would dare make such a ridiculous claim. His first impulse was to protest the tag's legitimacy, claiming I had only got him with one hand. My teammates all insisted the tag was good: \"Nah Willie, he got you with both hands.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-28-no8vi",
									"text": "So he was down, the touchdown was off, and Willie's team had to run another play from where I had made the tag. Willie was visibly angered--this kind of thing had never happened to him before in these school yard games. I was starting to build a bit of buzz--the new kid who caught Willie from behind--the new "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-29-ag6cw",
									"text": "white ",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-30-f8ila",
									"text": "kid who caught Willie from behind.\n\n"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-20-zoxbp",
									"href": "http://www.edline.net/pages/Cordova_Gardens_ES"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-23-k8bg6",
									"href": "http://www.cityofranchocordova.org/Index.aspx?page=22"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-31-l7bni",
									"href": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/basketball.jpg"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-33-pznxd",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/basketball.jpg?w=225",
								"url": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/basketball.jpg?w=225"
							},
							"alt": "photo of a basketball court"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-74-tuolg",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-34-9xwbv",
									"text": "Willie didn't like this change in his reputation. At our second, longer lunch recess I decided to play basketball. There wasn't a football game going, I didn't yet know anyone at the school, and basketball is an easy sport to play alone. I was shooting by myself at a basket when I felt a tap on my shoulder. It was Willie. \"Lemme have your ball,\" he said.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-35-fgu22",
									"text": "I was a little surprised--there was a whole rack of balls against a brick school wall maybe 50 yards away--what did he need mine for? I told him \"No--go get your own, they're right over there.\" He turned like he was going to get a ball, and then reared back and punched me hard--right in the mouth. He was wearing some kind of ring on his right hand, and it split my lip. I was stunned. It was the first time I had ever been punched in the face. I dropped my ball, and Willie scooped it up and started shooting baskets. He wasn't just a football prodigy. Whereas I had stood awkwardly, pushing the ball with both hands towards the basket, struggling just to get the ball to the rim while shooting, Willie had "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-37-dgqlk",
									"text": "exquisite form",
									"marks": [
										"key-36-8kc24"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-38-zllmh",
									"text": " on his jumper. He lined up, planted both feet, and just let the ball sail out of his hand, smooth as can be. I had never seen anything like it before from anyone my age. I stood near half court staring, transfixed by the grace of his game. Within a minute a teacher was on the scene--some kids had seen the punch, reported it to her, and she had come to investigate. My mouth was already starting swell up, and my split lip was oozing a little blood. \"What happened here?\" she asked.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-39-1wlkl",
									"text": "I stammered a bit before saying \"I was just playing basketball and then he came up [I still didn't know his name was Willie yet] and asked me for my ball. I told him no and then he punched me in the mouth.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-40-09zpz",
									"text": "Before she could say anything, another kid that I had never seen before came up and spoke, \"Nuh-uh Miss, that ain't true. Willie was just minding his business, and this "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-41-gwwvk",
									"text": "white boy",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-42-bxrcm",
									"text": " came up and hit him first and then Willie punched him back. He was just defending hisself.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-43-ncp3s",
									"text": "Miss obviously knew this boy, because she called him by name: \"Thank you, Donald. So you saw the fight?\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-44-m7a17",
									"text": "\"\"Yes, ma'am.\" The way he talked to Miss was sickeningly deferential.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-45-p61ka",
									"text": "Miss turned to me. \"Is that true?\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-46-1u4ra",
									"text": "\"No, no it isn't. I didn't hit anybody. I don't even know this boy. Either of them.\" I was near tears and my lip was thick and throbbing. It felt like dull meat when I rubbed my teeth over the fat part.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-47-z07mc",
									"text": "Miss knew the other boy, too and she called to him. \"Willie, come over here.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-48-qtbra",
									"text": "Willie dropped the ball and walked over to where we were standing, glaring at me as he came near. \"What?\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-49-tqrrh",
									"text": "\"I need you to come with me.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-50-84xb1",
									"text": "The four of us started walking. I didn't know where we were going or what was happening, but I felt like I was going to be in trouble, like this teacher believed the only eyewitness she had, and that something unjust was about to happen. Donald was the first one to speak. \"You taking us to the principal's office? Cuz I already told you, Willie didn't do nothing. That other boy hit him first and he was just defending himself.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-51-tlu7e",
									"text": "Miss didn't answer. We kept walking for another minute, leaving the playground altogether and coming inside the school. She stopped. We stopped. She looked at both of us, me with a fat lip and Willie with his angry, impenetrable face. It was clear to all of us that Willie was not going to speak unless forced to. She finally spoke. \"Willie, are you hurt?\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-52-v70y7",
									"text": "He shook his head. \"And you,\" she nodded in my direction, \"do you need to go to the nurse?\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-53-xhco2",
									"text": "I gulped and tongued my puffy lip. \"I don't think so. I think I'll be fine. Is it bleeding?\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-54-6su7a",
									"text": "She looked casually at my lip, \"No--just swollen. OK--Donald you can go.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-55-6gcm0",
									"text": "Donald hung around for a couple of seconds. \"But I saw the whole thing. I can be an eyewitness.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-56-qzrf6",
									"text": "Miss was firm. She fixed her eyes on him. \"I said, you can go.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-57-79hd5",
									"text": "He left. It was just me and Willie and Miss. We weren't walking anymore, and we didn't seem to be close to the principal's office. My impression of Miss was mostly that she didn't seem to talk much. Looking back, I think she was the kind of teacher who knew how to use silence as a way of opening disobedient kids up, the kind of woman who wasn't ever in any big hurry, but who made damn well sure she got to where she was going once she started going somewhere. I was starting to get a little panicky as the enormity of what I was involved in began to settle in on me. It was my first day at a new school and I had already been in a fight. Now we were going to go to the principal's office, and the principal was going to call my mom, and she would not be happy. I wasn't supposed to be getting into fights. I didn't get into trouble. I was taught to be a peacemaker.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-58-4syac",
									"text": "Miss spoke to Willie first. \"Willie, I don't care why you hit him or what he did to you. I don't ever want to see you fighting with this boy again. Do you understand me?\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-59-rzfbc",
									"text": "He nodded.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-60-kqcm1",
									"text": "\"You can go. I better not hear about you getting in another fight today. Alright?\" Her voice as she asked this last question was stern, and her eyes looked fierce, strong.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-61-h2065",
									"text": "Willie acknowledged this last question by popping his chin up slightly, setting his lower jaw and pinching his lips together. He turned and sauntered off.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-62-9tsx3",
									"text": "Miss waited until neither of us could see Willie. Her voice changed and she spoke to me with surprising kindness: \"Let me see that lip.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-63-7nh4v",
									"text": "I pursed my lips and leaned forward. She bent close and poked at it. \"It's swollen, and he split it pretty good, but it's not going to be too bad. Let's get you some ice.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-64-euszr",
									"text": "We turned and walked back towards the door we had entered, and turned down another hallway. I guessed that we were heading to the nurse's office. She spoke to me, \"I know you didn't hit Willie first. Donald was lying. I know that. I didn't take you two to the principal's office because the school rules say that anyone who hits another student gets suspended. Willie spends more time out of school than he does in school. Another suspension isn't going do any good for anybody. You think you can go the rest of the day without fighting with anyone else?\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-65-ex5rm",
									"text": "I told her I could, we got some ice, and I finished the day. I don't have any other memories of Willie, or Donald, and remarkably few other memories of the rest of that year. I remember a whole school assembly where one of the teachers got out a guitar, stood up in front of the whole auditorium, asked us all to come down in front of the stage and sit on the floor and then taught the whole school the lyrics to the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-67-uf6su",
									"text": "59th Street Bridge Song",
									"marks": [
										"key-66-g9v5t"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-68-nhm92",
									"text": ". I have no idea what pedagogical purpose this could possible have served, but I still remember just about the whole song. The very thought of the lines \"I'm dappled and drowsy and ready to sleep.\" and \"Slow down, you move too fast / You've got to make the morning last, / Skipping down the cobble stones, / Looking for fun and feeling groovy\" still fills me with a kind of thrilling nostalgia. I remember another time when a local police officer came (his visit was almost certainly part of a "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-70-saq2s",
									"text": "D.A.R.E.",
									"marks": [
										"key-69-3lkta"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-71-7tf55",
									"text": " program at my school) and covered a whole table with all manner of illegal drugs and terrified me with horror stories of what drug users do to themselves and others. I had never seen anything on the table before, but I could hear several of my classmates pointing and whispering to each other \"My mom has one of those\" or \"My mom's boyfriend used to leave that on the table sometimes.\"\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-72-hvtql",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_59\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\" caption=\"How I imagined a gang fight, circa 1989.\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-36-8kc24",
									"href": "http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rPWtdEDUS80"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-66-g9v5t",
									"href": "http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4KZi-aV0VTk"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-69-3lkta",
									"href": "http://www.dare.com/home/default.asp"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-73-fwb9m",
									"href": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/kid_imagined_gang_fight1.gif"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-75-2gogy",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/kid_imagined_gang_fight1.gif",
								"url": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/kid_imagined_gang_fight1.gif"
							},
							"alt": "Picture of Calvin &amp; Hobbes wrasslin"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-85-n4xhd",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-76-c4l7h",
									"text": "[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-77-o0u35",
									"text": "The last memory I have of going to school there is of a day when the bus taking me home after school was cancelled and I had to wait to get a ride from one of the teachers. We didn't leave school for more than an hour after school got out and she explained on the ride home that the bus couldn't come that day because there had been a gang fight between the Crips and the Bloods that started at high school football game nearby but spilled out and was roving through the streets. She added other salacious details, I'm sure, and I remember picturing hundreds of teenage kids in letter jackets (some blue and some red) hitting each other with lead pipes and brass knuckles and one of those dust cloud tornadoes that you see when cartoons fight, or when "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-79-nbdih",
									"text": "Pigpen",
									"marks": [
										"key-78-qiye4"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-80-71yx2",
									"text": " walked around in Peanuts.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-81-i1s80",
									"text": "So I starting by talking about sports and then I got distracted. All this to say, I'm playing basketball tonight, and I'm excited. I've started playing regularly with my friend Josh Kalscheur, a poet from Beaver Dam who is just finishing his MFA here at the UW-Madison. He's got a great basketball poem called "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-83-pkm9e",
									"text": "\"Throwdown\"",
									"marks": [
										"key-82-pq3rp"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-84-62j1g",
									"text": " over at Linebreak about a dunk attempt at a pickup game in Micronesia that includes these beautiful lines:"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-78-qiye4",
									"href": "http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PZ4c7E57P8Q"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-82-pq3rp",
									"href": "http://linebreak.org/poems/throwdown/"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-101-4ogis",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-86-7algl",
									"text": "... he dribbles\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-87-rcxmr",
									"text": "twice to his left and loops a no-look pass to himself, and if there’s a word\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-88-lhesl",
									"text": "for the curves he made, the arc and degrees of space in his wake, lost\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-89-1xic2",
									"text": "in the launch of it all, there was enough jump under the palms of his feet\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-90-ur486",
									"text": "for all the rolling eyes, all the bandannas flapping when he rushed break-\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-91-03d12",
									"text": "neck to the basket, the rock grinding to a halt on the touch before take-off,\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-92-c5g5j",
									"text": "the overcast background by his head, higher than any man, poster-high,\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-93-jhv8b",
									"text": "ladder-high, higher than their fathers’ hands, cupped on his forearm\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-94-m92v0",
									"text": "and cocked like a neck about to bite, the ball ripping over the rim\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-95-mhnoe",
									"text": "with sprays of rust-flecks and rotted wood, and a reverb of grunts\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-96-31xxi",
									"text": "makes its way in waves, and all the boys stand up, and all\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-97-wfnbg",
									"text": "the almost-dunkers, all the finger-tip rim touchers, the stilted wrists\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-98-cmdzq",
									"text": "and lead feet, all the stomping ones, the finesse boys with not-enough\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-99-g7ww2",
									"text": "ups or the right kicks, all the tall ones with no hops, all the jammed-thumbs,\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-100-xbb5t",
									"text": "they all watch the ball’s slow roll in the gravel, ..."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-115-zzw2d",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-102-fghtk",
									"text": "I think every athlete and even most spectators recognize the awe and grace in the moment Josh describes in this poem. I'm not a dunker--nobody at any of the pickup games I play in is, actually, but their is no paucity of moments of wordlessness in which bodies carry the \"arc and degrees of space in [their] wake.\" Even without dunk attempts, there's something about the social aspect of the game that appeals to me deeply, something about the fluidity of five players shifting and cutting, finding lanes and posting up, calling for the ball, driving hard to the rim or pulling up, something about the ball spinning in its beautiful arc towards the bottom of the net that is inescapably poetic. There's another basketball poem that I love written by another Madison poet, "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-104-jbpzo",
									"text": "Dennis Trudell",
									"marks": [
										"key-103-gm4zr"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-105-odxfr",
									"text": ". It's called \"The Jump Shooter\" and is the last poem in his book "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-107-fpnqk",
									"text": "Fragments in Us: Recent & Earlier Poems",
									"marks": [
										"em",
										"key-106-dhlmp"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-108-ltf7e",
									"text": ", which was selected by "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-110-i4wmk",
									"text": "Philip Levine",
									"marks": [
										"key-109-yfewa"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-111-rlryr",
									"text": " as the winner of the 1996 "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-113-i10zz",
									"text": "Felix Pollak Prize in Poetry",
									"marks": [
										"key-112-72gy2"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-114-td4wx",
									"text": ". Here it is:"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-103-gm4zr",
									"href": "http://www.dennistrudell.com/"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-106-dhlmp",
									"href": "http://books.google.com/books?id=QtqC9M-FBxcC&printsec=frontcover&dq=fragments+in+us+dennis+trudell&source=bl&ots=jYY2GIsNzT&sig=qNcCsMuBRwXJDdp02H0GiBooD3M&hl=en&ei=gu-uTebUJYTp0gG6jfHACw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-109-yfewa",
									"href": "http://www.poets.org/poet.php/prmPID/19"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-112-72gy2",
									"href": "http://uwpress.wisc.edu/FelixPollak.html"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-173-ip2ra",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-116-xtq2y",
									"text": "The way the ball\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-117-5uvx3",
									"text": "hung there\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-118-p373w",
									"text": "against the blue or purple\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-119-a8de0",
									"text": "one night last week\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-120-4hf9q",
									"text": "across town\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-121-aysew",
									"text": "at the playground where\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-122-itr5v",
									"text": "I had gone to spare\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-123-hekg0",
									"text": "my wife\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-124-ve0w0",
									"text": "from the mood I'd swallowed\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-125-hm4oh",
									"text": "and saw in the dusk\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-126-46yxf",
									"text": "a stranger\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-127-1vwur",
									"text": "shooting baskets a few\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-128-9pbb2",
									"text": "years older maybe\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-129-7bhtu",
									"text": "thirty-five\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-130-kvxhw",
									"text": "and joined him didn't\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-131-vxusr",
									"text": "ask or anything simply\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-132-cmm0r",
									"text": "went over\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-133-tjmge",
									"text": "picked off a rebound\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-134-1esmc",
									"text": "and hooked it back up\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-135-l5zs3",
									"text": "while he\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-136-o9oei",
									"text": "smiled I nodded and for\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-137-md5ug",
									"text": "ten minutes or so we\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-138-fjlxv",
									"text": "took turns\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-139-3f3vx",
									"text": "taking shots and the thing\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-140-jgvtp",
									"text": "is neither of us said\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-141-4bjzo",
									"text": "a word\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-142-wcyyr",
									"text": "and this fellow who's\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-143-ja2sf",
									"text": "too heavy now and slow\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-144-a52fn",
									"text": "to play\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-145-bfbqc",
									"text": "for any team still had\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-146-tcgmm",
									"text": "the old touch seldom\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-147-27n7j",
									"text": "ever missed\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-148-fcs3y",
									"text": "kept moving farther out\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-149-syw45",
									"text": "and finally his t-shirt\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-150-fmy31",
									"text": "a gray\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-151-9bxl0",
									"text": "and fuzzy blur I stood\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-152-egs2a",
									"text": "under the rim could\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-153-mqdnc",
									"text": "almost hear\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-154-qav8y",
									"text": "a high school cheer\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-155-aty5v",
									"text": "begin and fill a gym\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-156-7262a",
									"text": "while wooden\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-157-8oibn",
									"text": "bleachers rocked he made\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-158-gynri",
									"text": "three in a row from\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-159-0omdn",
									"text": "twenty feet\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-160-s2ty3",
									"text": "moved back two steps\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-161-t93bj",
									"text": "faked out a patch\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-162-1kurj",
									"text": "of darkness\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-163-f8b8f",
									"text": "arched another one and\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-164-8u8pu",
									"text": "the way the ball\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-165-91nvn",
									"text": "hung there\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-166-gmrvn",
									"text": "against the blue or purple\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-167-ax4b4",
									"text": "then suddenly filled\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-168-un5ga",
									"text": "the net\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-169-0to5h",
									"text": "made me wave goodbye\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-170-3fhk2",
									"text": "breathe deeply and begin\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-171-lov64",
									"text": "to whistle\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-172-72cw5",
									"text": "as I walked back home."
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-179-i7iio",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-174-e4g1z",
									"text": "Once again, there's a wordlessness and a sociality embedded in the memory of basketball, one that I find quite beautiful and true to my own experience. I played in a recent weekend tournament and the first team we faced was made up of a bunch of old men, mostly, some of whom resembled the protagonist in this poem, fellows who were: \"too heavy now and slow / to play / for any team,\" but to our chagrin, we discovered that even the fattest ones \"still had // the old touch seldom / ever missed.\" Despite our clear athletic advantage, we lost the game. Afterwards, my teammate "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-176-jys9d",
									"text": "Sam Crowfoot",
									"marks": [
										"key-175-hqc4e"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-177-slukl",
									"text": " reminded me that you never know with old guys, you've got to watch out for them, even if they don't look they've got anything left, because with old ballers the jumper is always the last thing to go. He said this with the knowing grin of a stone cold shooter, told me that the legs go quick, the belly usually follows soon after, but the jumper can stay sweet and pure for years.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-178-7zm44",
									"text": "At last Wednesday's game I took a elbow to the mouth hard, and my mouth got all swollen and bloody inside. It's mostly healed now, but I can still feel it, and it reminds me of Willie. I don't know where he's at, or what he's doing, or how, but I hope he's still got those moves, still shifty, still juking, still fresh & electric. I hope Willie can still pull up and rain down, that he's still got the touch. I don't imagine that Willie's had an easy life, and I wouldn't be surprised if most of the 4th grade magic and freedom he once had has long vanished from his life. And even though he punched me right in the face with a ring on his hand the first day we ever met, I don't hate him. He had a beautiful gift, and because I love the game, I'm happy to honor it, no matter how cankered or cruel the vessel may have been. In thinking about Willie, I really do hope that's Sam's right, that the jumper really is the last thing to go."
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-175-hqc4e",
									"href": "http://samcrowphoto.blogspot.com/"
								}
							]
						}
					]
				}
			},
			{
				"id": "posts:to-be-a-carer",
				"slug": "to-be-a-carer",
				"status": "published",
				"data": {
					"title": "To be a Carer",
					"featured_image": {
						"provider": "external",
						"id": "",
						"src": "https://steelwagstaff.info/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/iron-lung.jpg"
					},
					"content": [
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-7-eoawr",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-1-dymo4",
									"text": "I've been thinking a great deal lately about the medical profession, and more broadly, about health. I'm not certain why, particularly since I haven't been ill lately, and we tend usually to think of health and healers only when our body is not well, when we are in pain, when health eludes us. So I have been a little surprised by this turn in my thoughts towards a subject not often contemplated in this circumstances. The immediate cause may have been this short "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-3-rfril",
									"text": "mother-daughter exchange",
									"marks": [
										"key-2-gqdaj"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-4-6ylil",
									"text": " from StoryCorps, which I listened to earlier this week. There was something about the timbre of the mother's voice, and the daughter's, in this recording that pulled at me and that turned my thoughts towards the role of compassion in the medical profession, of the importance of emotional sensitivity in the work of healing.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-5-bthrv",
									"text": "[caption id=\"attachment_38\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\" caption=\"Girl in Iron Lung\"]"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-2-gqdaj",
									"href": "http://storycorps.org/listen/sarafina-viviano-and-her-mother-dana/"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-6-kjxik",
									"href": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/iron-lung.jpg"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "image",
							"_key": "key-8-737vf",
							"asset": {
								"_type": "reference",
								"_ref": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/iron-lung.jpg?w=300",
								"url": "http://steelwagstaff.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/iron-lung.jpg?w=300"
							},
							"alt": "Photograph of a young girl in an Iron Lung"
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-46-5m1n2",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-9-1qq6y",
									"text": "[/caption]\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-10-qsv9h",
									"text": "Usually when I think of doctors, I think first of my maternal grandfather, "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-12-5zil7",
									"text": "JD Mortensen",
									"marks": [
										"key-11-fhdcp"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-13-f1chj",
									"text": ". He was a "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-15-vga2s",
									"text": "doctor",
									"marks": [
										"key-14-r3qcy"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-16-ihv1f",
									"text": ", a cardiopulmonary surgeon who helped develop the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-18-ezgvk",
									"text": "IVOX machine",
									"marks": [
										"key-17-zm2dy"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-19-z14u4",
									"text": ", a "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-21-9x2lq",
									"text": "heart-lung machine",
									"marks": [
										"key-20-9pp34"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-22-hd544",
									"text": " meant to replace the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-24-r9q0w",
									"text": "Iron Lung",
									"marks": [
										"key-23-tpml6"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-25-2h7ol",
									"text": ". As a child, I always knew vaguely that grandpa was an important doctor, that he was considered excellent in his field, and heard bragging about his having invented something really amazing that could save and improve lives. I remember watching him being interviewed on a "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-27-9w96x",
									"text": "national early morning news show",
									"marks": [
										"key-26-mztax"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-28-7nl60",
									"text": " as a young child, not understanding a word of what he was saying, and still being awed and proud. In writing this post, I decided I wanted to learn more about his work, and more about Iron Lungs and other artificial heart-lung machines, since I knew next to nothing. I discovered that there are serious concerns about something called postperfusion syndrome, more commonly known as "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-30-m2mtx",
									"text": "\"pumphead\"",
									"marks": [
										"key-29-cglkr"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-31-zla4j",
									"text": ". I learned about two remarkable women who spent roughly six decades of their lives inside of iron lungs.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-32-zvcex",
									"text": "One was an Australian, "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-34-hraam",
									"text": "June Middleton",
									"marks": [
										"key-33-cm2hl"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-35-c63po",
									"text": ", who loved dancing, caught polio in her early 20s and then spent 16 hours a day inside her iron lung. At the time, she was engaged. Her partner stayed with her for five years after her paralysis, eventually moving on to another life and having a family of his own. In an interview near the end of her life she tells her interviewer that still loves him, that he was a great dancer, and that \"every day my feet itch to dance again.\" She had a dog named Angel as her companion, entered the Guinness Book of World Records in 2006, and "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-37-5rvsa",
									"text": "died",
									"marks": [
										"key-36-fw323"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-38-raolq",
									"text": " in 2009.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-39-ijkww",
									"text": "The other was "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-41-z97sx",
									"text": "Martha Mason",
									"marks": [
										"key-40-4fp6i"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-42-2pksm",
									"text": ", a woman from "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-44-xmopw",
									"text": "Lattimore, North Carolina",
									"marks": [
										"key-43-w2moy"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-45-bwfgq",
									"text": " (pop. 419) who contracted polio at age 11 following her older brother's death from the disease. Initially given about a year to live, she spent most the next 60 years in an Iron Lung. \"She survived, she later said, because she was endlessly curious and there was so much to learn.\" Ms. Mason \"chose to remain in an iron lung, she often said, for the freedom it gave her. It let her breathe without tubes in her throat, incisions or hospital stays, as newer, smaller ventilators might require. It took no professional training to operate, letting her remain mistress of her own house, with just two aides assisting her.\" In many ways she was a kind of social hub for the town, who took care of her:"
								}
							],
							"markDefs": [
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-11-fhdcp",
									"href": "http://www.deseretnews.com/article/1335370/Obituary-JD-Mortensen-MD.html"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-14-r3qcy",
									"href": "http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,936119,00.html"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-17-zm2dy",
									"href": "http://books.google.com/books?id=spMIiM7AkaUC&pg=PA258"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-20-9pp34",
									"href": "http://www.cts.usc.edu/zglossary-heartlungmachine.html"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-23-tpml6",
									"href": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron_lung"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-26-mztax",
									"href": "https://docs.google.com/document/d/1_8M-iJu25OW804hMU6nrjIFhYrNkEXNYlI7o-7wvPlQ/edit?hl=en"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-29-cglkr",
									"href": "http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=pumphead-heart-lung-machine&print=true"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-33-cm2hl",
									"href": "http://www.smh.com.au/national/robbed-of-movement-the-dance-of-life-goes-on-20081228-767y.html"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-36-fw323",
									"href": "http://www.smh.com.au/national/dead-after-60-years-in-iron-lung-20091101-hqyy.html?autostart=1"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-40-4fp6i",
									"href": "http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/10/us/10mason.html"
								},
								{
									"_type": "link",
									"_key": "key-43-w2moy",
									"href": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lattimore,_North_Carolina"
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-51-oa0a2",
							"style": "blockquote",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-47-r68s9",
									"text": "\"If Ms. Mason could not go to the town, then the town was quite prepared to come to her. The doctor visited regularly, of course, but so did all the neighbors and the neighbors’ neighbors. So did members of the local fire department, who came by during power failures to make sure her backup generator was working.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-48-nkkyn",
									"text": "Ms. Mason often gave dinner parties — she ate lying down, with her guests around the table and the iron lung pushed up beside it — and savored lively conversation, good gossip and the occasional bawdy story. Amid the rhythmic "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-49-mdiyg",
									"text": "whoosh ... whoosh",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-50-otfu9",
									"text": " of the iron lung, the local book club met in her home.\""
								}
							]
						},
						{
							"_type": "block",
							"_key": "key-123-iw220",
							"style": "normal",
							"children": [
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-52-jv950",
									"text": "She was an intellectual in a small town, which must have often meant being lonely and longing for things she could not find or know, but which was made considerably easier in the mid-1990s when she obtained a voice-activated computer with internet access. In some ways her story reminds me of the story of "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-54-32srm",
									"text": "Andrew Monkelban",
									"marks": [
										"key-53-tzhc3"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-55-i5fck",
									"text": ", a man with cerebral palsy featured in the recent documentary "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-57-x4urh",
									"text": "Second Skin",
									"marks": [
										"em",
										"key-56-6aaoj"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-58-8qfu7",
									"text": ", who describes how participation in virtual worlds through online gaming allows him to feel differently embodied, liberated, and more free. The film is streaming on Netflix Instant if you have a subscription, and his segment is at the 1:12:30 mark, I think. You can see a trailer "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-60-foeq5",
									"text": "here",
									"marks": [
										"key-59-xnkl8"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-61-ryxob",
									"text": ".\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-62-q9832",
									"text": "My grandfather was an early hero of mine, and his life has exerted an enormous influence over his descendents, which include 9 children, a step-child and upwards of 50 grandchildren. One of his sons became an obstetrician in Logan, Utah, where he has delivered thousands of Cache County babies. Another is an ophthalmologist in Salt Lake City. Other of his children have gone on to prominence and success in their chosen fields, and all of them were marked in several ways by their relationship to JD. Grandpa was the most driven man I've ever known, deeply dedicated to work, vigorous, resolute, and even obstinate in his pursuit of excellence in several disparate facets of his life. He sometimes felt gruff, emotionally distant, and even forbidding, but nearly everyone in his family still sought his approval for their life, their work, and their choices, and many measured their lives against his. To me, he filled the role of the mostly benevolent patriarch, and I loved, admired, and respected him. Near the end of his life he authored (with the help of a secretary and the transcription efforts of my mother, among others) a beautiful two-volume history of his life, and then having completed that project, turned to write similar histories for his mother, his first wife, Sarah Owens (who died of cancer in 1969), and his second wife, Eva Tanner, a native of "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-64-nlb2z",
									"text": "Grouse Creek, Utah",
									"marks": [
										"key-63-qxj6c"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-65-sl54o",
									"text": " and the woman I knew as grandma throughout my life. These documents have been invaluable for me as a source of family history and as a means of humanizing individuals whom I knew only in part, or never met, but who were important members of my family's past, and who form key parts of my own heritage.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-66-0vhzi",
									"text": "Despite my grandfather's influence (or perhaps because of it), I have never myself wanted to be a physician, or to work in the medical professions. I think my only natural qualification for the trade would be my abysmal handwriting. The closest I've ever come to the work is through volunteering at nursing homes, singing and visiting patients at hospitals, or helping with hospice care programs. I have never been able to offer any wisdom or insight about the body and its functioning, but I have been able to choose to be present for those who have been in extreme pain, who have been approaching death, and who have been subject to the frequent injustices of chronic illness, suffering, and even terminal disease. I think that one of the deepest lessons for me in these experiences has been that health is in itself an almost wholly veiled mystery, one that is too infrequently appreciated and poorly understood by a broader culture which seeks for dozens of distractions to escape the act of giving attention to the body, which is desperate not to listen to the body's signals, rhythms, and irregularities. Too often we abuse ourselves, permit others to misuse or mistreat us, and sometimes even fall victim to unwanted and unjust woundings. When this happens we feel uncertain how to recover health, how to be made whole, or failing that, at least functional. And this is where I think that medicine and health systems often enter our lives.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-67-4bu55",
									"text": "Though I have no desire in becoming a health care professional, my youngest sister is training to become a nurse. She told me she felt called to the profession, and once admitted that she didn't really love the work, but felt for some reason like it was what she was supposed to do with her life. The idea of being called to nurse other human lives touches me, as does the idea of responding "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-69-m6vat",
									"text": "to such a call",
									"marks": [
										"key-68-xgzrk"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-70-xpvr3",
									"text": ". I want to write more about this idea in another post, so I'll leave it for now. What I want to explore more deeply is the complexity and limits of nursing, of the more fundamental aspects of care-giving and care-receiving that make up the human and social networks of health in our own communities that we ought to be intimately concerned and involved with. When I was 19 years old, I left school (I had just completed my freshman year at Brigham Young University) to serve a two-year proselyting mission for the LDS church in the northeast part of England. I moved around every few months, and the longest time I spent in any one place was in Sheffield. I lived with three other missionaries in a small apartment near a large council estate in Fox Hill, on the top of Browning Street and we attended church with the Sheffield 2nd ward. I'm not sure what it was about the place, or that congregation, but I loved that area and that ward more deeply than anywhere else I lived on my mission. I think in part it was the relatively deep familiarity I gained with prolonged exposure, but I also think there were other things at play. One curious feature of that ward is that probably a dozen or more of the women who attended services there worked in the medical profession in some capacity. Many worked as what we would call nurses in the States, but there the were known (and referred to themselves) as \"carers\". I looked up the word in a "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-72-8xaor",
									"text": "free online dictionary",
									"marks": [
										"key-71-gbhfq"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-73-xutwy",
									"text": " to check my memory, and it gives the definition as \"a person who has accepted responsibility for looking after a vulnerable neighbour or relative.\" Such a definition stuns me with its accuracy and its enormity. I think in hindsight that one reason I loved Sheffield so much was that I was in regular contact with a group of people who had disproportionately accepted responsibility for looking after the vulnerable. How can one not be transformed by such proximity?\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-74-ldpze",
									"text": "When I was an undergraduate, in the first creative writing class I ever took, Shannon Castleton, my instructor, asked us to read Richard Selzer's story "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-76-06lfp",
									"text": "\"The Knife\"",
									"marks": [
										"key-75-vaxwm"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-77-ytv0m",
									"text": ". It conquered me, completely. I later read several other of his stories (my favorites are probably "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-79-lh1a1",
									"text": "\"Imelda\"",
									"marks": [
										"key-78-7njtq"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-80-napjr",
									"text": " and "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-82-agzk0",
									"text": "\"Mercy\"",
									"marks": [
										"key-81-bbqrw"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-83-4namd",
									"text": ") and admired his gifts of description, compassion, and his human concern for his own practice of medicine and the health of his patients. It was very different from the medicine practiced by the country doctor in William Carlos Williams' "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-85-8140u",
									"text": "\"The Use of Force\"",
									"marks": [
										"key-84-8zgvw"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-86-eo70y",
									"text": " and I saw an intelligent, feeling man seeking to wrestle with the complexities incumbent in the decision to accept responsibility for looking after those who are vulnerable, many of the same feelings I had when I watched Michael Moore's moving interview with "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-88-4bf0u",
									"text": "Aleida",
									"marks": [
										"key-87-30dcm"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-89-folxd",
									"text": " "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-91-qdw03",
									"text": "Guevara",
									"marks": [
										"key-90-rrem0"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-92-pbsmy",
									"text": " in his film "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-93-8l4s3",
									"text": "Sicko ",
									"marks": [
										"em"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-94-i5qxe",
									"text": "[see "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-96-hrqe3",
									"text": "part 1",
									"marks": [
										"key-95-3r52v"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-97-ictr4",
									"text": " & "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-99-6jnzj",
									"text": "part 2",
									"marks": [
										"key-98-ydeok"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-100-5g1fj",
									"text": "]. A few years later I was reading through an anthology of poetry about work and found a few poems by a woman who had worked as a nurse named "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-102-wk3ca",
									"text": "Belle Waring",
									"marks": [
										"key-101-ro66w"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-103-x53gc",
									"text": ". Her writing pierced me, and I felt directly appellated, gripped, undone. A few of her poems are online, like "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-105-jhshs",
									"text": "\"The Forgery\" & \"Saudade\"",
									"marks": [
										"key-104-nt6ow"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-106-3d0nq",
									"text": ", the heartbreaking "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-108-e736r",
									"text": "\"It Was My First Nursing Job\"",
									"marks": [
										"key-107-45mrm"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-109-gpi9u",
									"text": " (at the bottom of the page, after the book review), and "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-111-4ok9n",
									"text": "\"Our Lady of the Laundromat\"",
									"marks": [
										"key-110-3wwfy"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-112-q1n3v",
									"text": ". Read her work. When I started as a co-curator of the "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-114-hyepx",
									"text": "FELIX",
									"marks": [
										"key-113-i8ctf"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-115-dp288",
									"text": " reading series, she was the first poet that I wanted to invite, but I was never able to locate her. Writing this post has brought her back to mind, and I hope that I will be able to find her, convince my co-curators and her to come to Madison, meet her, and hear her poetry performed in person.\n\n"
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-116-ugk38",
									"text": "In addition to these storyteller-physicians and poet-nurses, I am compelled by the example of all manner of healers and carers who \"draw out their souls to the hungry, and satisfy the afflicted\" (Isaiah 58:10), who seek for ways to build up the old waste places, who yearn (and work) to be \""
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-118-550gt",
									"text": "repairers of the breach",
									"marks": [
										"key-117-5bdoo"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-119-5d5rs",
									"text": ", restorers of paths to dwell in\" (Isaiah 58:12). I loved reading the story of Driggs, Idaho native "
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-121-8j3me",
									"text": "David Rakel",
									"marks": [
										"key-120-jp7is"
									]
								},
								{
									"_type": "span",
									"_key": "key-122-0dccn",
									"text": ", a tenured professor at UW-Madison's medical school, who has done much to practice good wisdom around health and to incorporate holistic, integrated medicine into the community I live in. Practitioners of the kind of integrative medicine he teaches \"are schooled in ways to hold on to their hearts and souls even as they master the intricacies of anatomy, physiology, biology, and psychology. They see their work as healing the whole patient, rather than being limited to specific body parts\". In a recent co-authored article Rakel wrote:"
								}
							],
